deck_excerpt: Kaijus with control elements and OTK opprotunities because of Fossils
deck_description: So this is my first upload. I've been trying to make a real Kaiju Deck that can be effective for a while now. All the decks I've found that had Kaiju in the description just had like 2 Kaijus max (not a Kaiju deck to me sorry). This started out as a control deck. It still has some of the control elements but with the fossil cards it now also has some agression behind it. The White Aura Whale is supposed to be Fossil Machine Skull Convoy. I've been having a lot of success with this deck lately, the it's only downsides are that when you get somewhat of a dead hand (which doesn't happen often but still) it bricks big time! That's why I added pot of desires for draw power, although I wish I could have picked something else because there is always the danger that you can banish some key card that you need right now by accident (and also because of the pot this deck is 41 cards, which the perfectionist in me kind of hates...). The main strategy should be to not go overboard, but be agressive at the right moment. The Fossil Fusion Monsters can deliver OTKs pretty quickly, so if you put them on the field at the right moment and have some Kaiju here and there as well you are good to go (I love to have Gameciel with Waterfront together with Skull Convoy on the field, it's such a good and simple board). About the side deck: I do have some cards in there but some of the are just fillers and I'm not really sure what would be best to put there (also I couldn't figure out how to add cards to the side deck in this Deck Builder ooops). Anyways, I hope ya'll like it and are able to have fun with this deck, especially those people that really wanted a deck that makes Kaijus shine.

This deck does great against synchro decks in general because of some of  the effects of Meklord monsters that specifically target synchro monsters. In this deck there are 3 main monster. There's really no strat you just have to learn how to use this deck the way you like playing yugioh. Enjoy(:

deck_description: I made this deck today since I was bored and wanted to make a deck that people didn't much about. What I found with testing is that Simorgh, Bird of Bringing is a one card tribute summon. You summon it to the field and use it's effect to search for the field spell Elborz, the Sacred Lands of Simorgh. You than use the field spell to allow you to tribute summon a monster for one less monster and than use its other effect to summon that one by tributing Simorgh, Bird of Bringing.

deck_name: Adamancipator Sky Striker- Post Banlist Dec 2020
deck_excerpt: Sky Strikers mixed together with Adamancipators to spam out monsters.
deck_description: So i've been trying to find two cool archetypes for both of these decks to mash together, and I realized I can just mash both of these together.  These two work surprisingly well together and are super fun to play. Also, by the way, my posts and such might be sparratic for the rest of this month; busy with the holidays.  Deck guide 3x Analyzer- Analyzer is the main starter card for the Adamancipator, as his special summoning  condition is easy. As long as you search him or see him in your opening hand, you can special him to proc the other's effects to special the rest. That leaves your Normal Summon open for the Sky Strikers, who need it. Aditionally, Analyzer does the funky excavation, to search out and special the rocks for quick synchros.  2x Seeker- Seeker is another one of the Adamancipator's, which you want to special summon off of having Anaylzer on the field and SS'd, so you can special summon Seeker easily. Then, like Analyzer, you can excevate and get out even more rocks for more synchros.  2x Researcher- Like Seeker, Researcher is very easy to get out as long as you've gotten off Analyzer and Seeker. And like the others, she does the funky excavation and special summoning of the rocks, allowing you to go into more synchros quickly and build up your board.  2x Leonite- Leonite is the first crystal, and allows you to recover your Ada resources, albeit slowly, as you put the GY ones on top of the deck (you will never be putting ones from the hand on top). It also allows you to bounce back Leonite 2: Electric Boogaloo to topdeck itself, but that's a really bad effect.  2x Dragite- When being summoned by one of the excevation effects, it draws a card, which is pretty nice as long as you top deck something to extend plays. Similarly to Leonite, it allows you to bounce back Dragite 2: Electric Boogaloo to the extra deck to top deck itself, but that's still a really bad effect. 1x Raptite- On summon of an excevation effect, it allows you to topdeck one of the Adamancipator's in your grave, so it's a slower revival effect basically. And, like the rest, he has the shitty bounce effect.  3x Raye- Raye is one of the key cards of the Sky Striker strat, as it's also the deck's main normal summon. It leads straight into any of the Links, and on summon, can also get out Roze alongside herself for either a link-2 or two Sky Strikers. And in the grave, it can (slowly) recover itself if one of your Links is destroyed, to lead into another Sky Striker link.  3x Roze- As long as you normal summon a Raye, you can special out a Roze alongside her. Roze allows you to either go into Zeke, or two Sky Striker link-1's, which is quite nice to all have out for field swarming capabilites. And when an opponent's monster in the Extra Monster zone leaves the field, she can special summon herself and negate a opponent's monsters effect. While this can be more situational due to us being in Master Rule 5, it's still fairly strong. 3x Gamma- Gamma is the deck's main hand trap, as it can negate literally anything and get a body on the field doing so. The main drawback of Gamma is that it requires a garnet (Driver), but Driver at 1 means it's rare to draw into it and easier to use Gamma and recycle Driver.  1x Driver- A shitty garnet for Gamma. It doesn't even look cool like other Garnets.  3x Lapuite- Lapuite is the deck's main field spell, but can be swapped out for Mystic Mine in some situations if neccesary. Lapuite boosts the already fairly strong power of your Adamancipators, allowing you to do high damage. Additonally, after you perform your combos and such, you can top deck 5 Adamancipator cards to make even more Synchros and such if your opponent still isn't dead after that turn. 3x Friends- Friends is the deck's main searcher for the Adamancipators, as it allows you to get whichever Rock you need that's excevated. Friends can be a bit of a pain, as you need a few Rocks out to use it optimally, but it's still fairly solid. Although, Friends is also xenophobic, locking you into Rocks for the rest of the turn, meaning you need to do your Sky Strikers first. Some variants may want to cut down on the Friends, if they're going more heavily into the Sky Strikers.  2x Signs- Signs allows you to revive your monsters or extend your plays, whichever you need. You can revive your fallen Adamancipator Synchros that you actually want on the field, that were destroyed or something of the sort, to re-activate their effects and such. Or you can use it to re-summon the monsters you used for a synchro summon, in order to extend your plays.  1x Multirole- Multirole allows you to give your spells protection, which is a great effect since the Spells are really vital for the Sky Striker strategy. Additionally, it allows you to set a ton of spells from your grave during the end phase, which, depending on the combos you did, can be a huge set up and can heavily interrupt the opponent's plays.  2x Afterburners- Afterburners gives some fairly nice monster removal to get rid of the opponent's monsters and clear the field for an OTK. It also allows you to remove some backrow if it's fairly late into the Spell cycle.  1x Hornet Drones- Hornet Drones allows you to get out a token for a quick Link, adding onto the amount of Sky Striker Link field swarming you can get in order to have a quick OTK and/or grind out the game.  3x Shark Cannon- Shark Cannon allows you to get your opponent's key combo pieces out of play in order to heavily interrupt their plays, which is a great and solid effect on a quick play (which you can set with Multirole to fuck them over when they try making a comeback). Additionally, if you're heavily into the spell cycle, you can steal the monster.  3x Widow Anchor- Widow Anchor is basically a better Effect Veiler, allowing you to negate a problem monster's effects and get it out of the way in order to make your plays easier to pull off. Additionally, as long as you use Widow Anchor late into the spell cycle, you can steal the monster with no restrictions (aside from being destroyed in the end phase), meaning if it's a high attack monster you can easily push for game with it. You can also set it with Multirole to heavily interrupt your opponent's plays.  Extra deck Dragite- Dragite is the deck's main Synchro boss monster, that you want to focus on getting out with the Adamancipators. It allows non targeting, not destruction removal, just by excevating cards (which benefits you) which in the current game is absolutely amazing and can clear out entire boards. And, as long as you have the original main deck Dragite in the grave, you can negate any card effect your opponent activates, which is also amazing.  2x Leonite- Leonite allows you to search and is basically an archetypal Rota, being a Friend's with much less restrictions. Additionally, during the opponent's turn, as long as you have the original Leonite in the grave, you can special any Rock monster. This allows you to even recover the Synchros or extend plays, which is great.  1x Raptite- Raptite allows you to get out more Rock monsters onto the field, helping to Synchro climb into Dragite. Additionally, during the opponent's turn, as long as you have the original Raptite in the grave, you can banish an opponent's card from the grave, which can heavily interrupt plays.  2x Kagari- Kagari allows you to recover your important spells and re-use them, recurring resources with ease. Kagari also grows to be a big beater as long as you have spells in the grave, which you should have.  2x Kaina- Kaina gives you a psuedo attack stun, which isn't super helpful, but can be somewhat helpful in some situations when you need to launch a comeback. She also gives you a very small LP recovery when you activate a Sky Striker spell, although that can add up to a big number.  2x Shizuku- Shizuku cripples the opponent's board, as you should have tons of spells in the grave, making it much easier to run over and finish the game. Additionally, it can search out the Sky Striker spells you need for your next turn if your opponent isn't dead by then.  2x Zeke- Zeke is the deck's main link-2, which is made with Roze and Raye instead of just Raye. He gives you easy, non destruction removal, which is really strong. Additionally, Zeke can gain high levels of attack, growing even stronger for an OTK.  2x Hayate- Hayata can attack directly, which is fantastic for the deck, as it allows you to chip away at the opponent and help with finishing them off. Additionally, Hayate can send a Sky Striker spell from grave once it attacks, providing more fodder and set up for Multirole. Playing guide The deck mainly operates with activating the Sky Striker spells immediately, as at the start of their turn they shouldn't control any main zone monsters. Afterwards, you need you summon out Analyzer and get out the other Adamancipator's by their conditions. Then, you normal summon out the Ace's. And after excevating heavily and setting up your board, you can link away the Ace's into the Link's to prop their effects, and Synchro climb into the Synchros. After that, you want to continually attack at your opponent non-stop, until you grind them down.

deck_excerpt: Summon Dark Magician and Magician of Chaos to clear opponent's's field by destroying or banishing their cards
deck_description: This deck is focused around getting materials for ritual summoning and then with almost the same material you use MoC's effect to destroy opponent's cards.  Your main boss monster is Magician of Chaos, but you can also bring out Chaos MAX Dragon or Magician of Black Chaos MAX     This deck doesn't use Dragoon because I dislike that card even though it would probably make this deck a bit stronger. Besides, the main focus isn't on the Extra Deck     Your main way to summon your ritual (and some fusion monsters) is by using Secrets of Dark Magic which you can search with Magician's Rod. You can also use classic ritual support (Manju, Impcantation, Preperation of Rites etc.)  need to get what you need.     With Eternal Soul you can revive DM or CoM, after it is destroyed or tributed     If you activate CoM's effect on opponent's turn you can destroy Artifact Scythe to prevent your opponent from using the Extra Deck     Extra Deck is made out of generic DM and not-DM cards which you can bring out relatively easy considering that the Extra Deck isn't that important for the deck (besides maybe Dark Magicians and Ebon Illusion). So don't worry about Extravigance. But I did add Quintet and Magicalized Fusion to flex on people :)

deck_excerpt: Control Traptrix with a Eldlich engine for even more Control.
deck_description: So here's a more control oriented deck with the Eldlich man himself and the control loli's, so double the waifu's. It's a going first control deck, oriented on making sure the opponent isn't allowed to do anything the entire time and then wittling their life points down slowly. Credit to the dude who's trying way too hard to be like TeamSam, AKA Yugituber  for giving me the idea. Also, this utilizes the OCG support so you may have to wait to play the full deck. Ratio update: Cut 1 Black Awakening for an extra Eldland. Also just now realized this is technically meta because of Eldlich. Update 2: Cut 1 Nepnethes and 1 Conquistador for a Sangquine. You're welcome TeamSam but worse. Deck guide 3x Eldlich the Golden Lord- The main boy, he's finally dropped a lot in price, making this deck (somewhat) more budget friendly in some places. Anyway, Eld is great, as he gives non-destruction removal for a ton of your opponent's problem cards and sets up your grave. Additionally, he has a great special summoning condition that's easy to fulfill and loads up your grave with spells and traps to recover later. Also, he gives off the vibes of a JoJo's villain. Someone, please give him a Stand.  3x Atrax- Atrax helps a lot with your Holes (hee hee), as it allows you to activate them from the hand, meaning you don't have to set them and have them sitting there and be hit by S/T removal. She also makes it so your your Hole's can't be negated, which is also great, considering the current format is very heavy with negates like Gamma.  2x Dionea- Dionea recovers the monsters you need, helping to build up into the XYZ or links to build up your backrow and such mid to late game. Additionally, when it's special summoned, it recovers all the Hole's you've used or sent for Eldlich, allowing you to reuse them even more and pressure your opponent.  3x Myrmeleo- Myrmeleo fetches most of the traps you need, so you can set up your backrow and/or provide fodder for Eldlich in order to get him out onto the field and set up your grave. Additionally,  if it's special summoned, it can pop some  backrow, which can be helpful in some situations.  3x Mantis- Mantis searches out all the Traptrix monsters you need for your plays, mainly Ginalloa since Mantis takes up your normal summon. Additionally, Mantis allows you to bounce back your dead backrow in order to replace it with better backrow that's of use.  3x Ginalloa- One of the new pieces of OCG support, Ginalloa helps greatly with swarming the field and going into the XYZ/Links. Her first effect allows you to send backrow to grave to special summon her, which can set up your grave with Eldlich backrow and such. Additionally, she can banish herself from grave to re-set backrow from the grave. Although, you can only do one of these effects once per turn, which is a bit annoying. 2x Genlisea- Genlisea is a great card for setting up huge amounts of backrow mid-to late game, in case your opponent is trying to push to make a board, so you can force them into your favored gamestate. Genlisea tributes herself to set 2 Hole traps with different names, one from deck and one from grave, which is great for recovering resources and setting up a huge backrow.  3x Nephetes- Nephetes helps a lot with swarming the field as you activate the Holes, as when you activate a Hole she allows you to special a Traptrix from deck, helping to swarm the field and lead into link and XYZ plays.  2x Cursed Eldland- Cursed Eldland searches out Eldlich and all of his backrow for a miniscule cost of life points, which is a great effect for filling the gaps in your hand. Additionallky, when it leaves the field, it allows you to set Eldlich backrow directly from deck, which is also fantastic.  3x Black Awakening- Black Awakening helps with getting out Eldlich as fast as possible, and it helps as it doesn't require his cost of sending backrow to grave. It can also let you get multiple Eldliches onto field, which is great. And you can banish it from the grave to set a Golden Land trap directly from deck to backrow, helping heavily with the control focus. Although, you can only use on of these effects per turn, so it's your choice. You can set a Black Awakening and send it off of Eldlich and then banish Black Awakening for it's set, so that's a pretty cool combo. Also, for budget decks, you can replace this with White Destiny.  3x Trap Hole Nightmare- Trap Hole Nightmare is more so a backrow Effect Veiler, as it's insurance in case your opponent gets through your Trap Holes. When they try to activate their monster effects, you can punish them and interrupt them even more.  3x Bottomless Trap Hole- Bottomless Trap Hole is one of the deck's main backrow, as it's heavily searchable and recyclable. You want to constantly use it on your opponent's monsters, making sure they waste resources on plays and then you completely disrupt those plays.  2x Gravedigger's- Gravedigger's heavily counters hand traps, GY decks, and banishing decks, as whenever your opponent activates a card in hand, GY, or a banished card, you can negate it and inflict 2000 burn. 2000 burn is massive for a deck that runs small monsters and has to chip away at the opponent, and Gravedigger's can protect your plays from hand traps or can compeletely stop GY decks.  2x Golden Land Forever!- Golden Land Forever is one of the deck's main negates, as you can tribute an Eldlich to negate any effect. This is fantastic for more heavy interruptions, and the cost of tributing Eldlich isn't very major because of how heavily recycable Eldlich is. Additionally, it's heavily searchable in the deck.  3x Conquistador- Conquistador serves as a wall of 1800, and heavily interrupts your opponent's plays as long as you have Eldlich out on the field, as it allows you to destroy one of the opponent's cards, without targeting, which is great in the current meta. and you can banish it to set a Eldlixer spell directly from deck, allowing you to swarm the field with even more Eldliches. You can only use one of these effect's per turn, but it's still great.  The extra deck 3x Allomerus- Allomerus helps to recover monsters and build up your board heavily, which can allow you to build up into the links and push for game mid- to late game once your opponent has exhausted all of their resources. You can detacth 2 materials from Allo to special a Traptrix from grave, which is pretty nice for leading into Sera for more plays. Additionally, if an opponent's monster is destroyed/banished by one of our card effects, you can steal it with no restrictions. That's amazing, as you can easily steal a huge monster.  2x Rafflesia- Rafflesia gives complete protection to all your Traptrix (except itself) from battle and card effects, which is great due to their low stats and lack of built in protection. Additionally, Rafflesia allows you  to load up your grave with Hole traps and copies their effects, making it a Hole on legs and can completely force the gamestate into your favor.  2x Urticularia- Urticularia allows you to re-use all your trap holes, as they reset themselves instead of going to the grave. There is no restrictions on this, which is amazing, as it allows you to keep a strong backrow and not have to recur your resources from grave. And, during the end phase, it has a Gantala style effect, where it specials a Traptrix from grave, which helps a lot with field swarming.  3x Sera- Sera is annoyingly expensive, but completely worth it. When you activate the Holes, you can special a Traptrix from deck, which can lead to a huge amount of Traptrix on grave and can lead to a ton of field presence and a massive board depending on how your turn goes. Additionally, when another Traptrix monster activates it's effect, you can set a Hole straight from deck to the backrow, which is also great for setting up a huge board/backrow. 2x Pheonix- Pheonix is pretty much just here to make use of some of the swarming potential you can have, and to clear backrow when neccesary. Also here to fill the extra deck. 2x Unicorn- Unicorn is a solid card for mid-to late game when you have a good amount of monsters on the field for a Link summon, so you can get the opponent's monsters out of the way in order to push for game. Playing guide So, the deck is mainly a going first control/stun deck, although that should be obvious. You want to go first and use your normal summon on something like Myrmello or whichever Traptrix you have in hand at the time, in order to set up your field and get off their effects. Afterwards, you want to use Eldlich's effect to summon himself (or search him or summon him directly from the deck), and then set up your backrow. After that, you simply just Trap Hole everything the opponent tries and make sure they can't do anything, also forcing them to expend their resources on trying to push through, and then negating the push with things like Golden Land Forever. Mid- to late game, once you've set up a board, you want to link it away into the Traptrix Links and overlay some into the XYZ, and use the Extra Deck Traptrix to grind out the game until you finally wittle them down and push for game.  (things to note: This deck hates going first, and Mystic Mine is something you should use in the side deck for some match ups.) Any suggestions or anything is appreciated. Thank you for reading!

deck_excerpt: Lightsworns and Shaddols mashed together to mill a ton and make big monsters.
deck_description: So, credit to Team Sam Two: Self Advertisement Boogaloo for the idea. This is a fairly fun mix of archetypes, as the milling of Lightsworns props the effects of the Shaddols and can lead into some strong fusions and Extra deck monsters to push for game. They also both have really cool lore, art, and theming. Deck guide 3x General- General allows you to basically fill up your banished pile, and cripple an opponent's monster's stats by doing so, which is very helpful for running over problem monsters and for pushing for game mid to late game.  3x Raiden- Raiden is mainly used for it's strong mill, as all in all, it allows you to mill 4 cards during your turn, which can easily prop the effects of a ton of Lightsworns and Shaddols. It also loads up your grave yard for other plays, allowing you to do even more stuff. 3x Lumina- Lumina is a great card for extending the deck's plays and leading into XYZ and the usch, as you can banish normally non-special summonable Lightsworns from your hand to then re-special summon them. And, when another Lightsworn activates it's effect, you can mill 3. This is great with cards like Felis and Raiden, as with Felis it unclogs your hand and gives you removal with a mill of 6; with Raidin, it gives you a mill of 5 and can lead into either Curious or Michael.  1x Felis- Felis is best  to keep in deck to be milled or summoned off of Lumina. When milled, she allows you to special summon herself.   Felis gives you a pop for the opponent and  then mill's 3, activating a ton of Shaddol effects and filling up your grave.  1x Beast- Beast gives some small draw power when sent to the grave, which isn't major but still can be fairly nice.  2x Squamata- When it's sent, Squamata allows you to send more Shaddol cards from deck to grave. This is great because it activates their effects for whatever you need, and fills up your grave for later plays.  2x Wendi- Wendi helps with field swarming and getting more mosnters on board for fusions. You can also use the face downs to actually activate their flip effects sometimes, although you're better off just fusing them away.  2x Hedghehog- Hedghehog fetches all the Shaddol monsters you need for fusions and such, as it fills the gaps in your hand when sent to the grave. Hedghehog is generally pretty fantastic.  2x Keios- Keios helps to buff up your monsters when you're trying to push for game, as it helps to raise their attack stats to run over large monsters or deal a ton of damage. Additionally, Keios props the effects of other Shaddols.  3x Ryko- Ryko gives you non-targeting, non destruction removal at the small cost of banishing a Lightsworn (which can easily be got back by Lumina), which in the current game is fantastic. It also mills 3 when a Lightsworn activate's its effect, which is great for milling a ton.  3x Ash- You should know why I play this by know.  3x Charge- Charge is an amazing card in this deck and a staple 3 of. It's cost is pure plussing, as it mills three without taking up a summon and fills up your grave with propping Shaddol effects. And if it's uninterrupted, Charge adds a Lightsworn monster to fill in the gaps of your hand. 2x Solar Recharge- Solar Recharge is a great draw spell, as it's a nice draw 2 and mill's 2 to activate Shaddol effects, all at the cost of discarding a single Lightsworn (which is why it's at 2), which can be used to set up your grave for other plays.  3x Nephe- Nephe is a great card for summoning a lot of the Fusions, as it alters the attributes of your Shaddols so you can properly fuse into a lot of the Shaddol fusions that require specific attributes. Nephe also allows you to fuse into a Shaddol monster with the equipped monster and monsters on field/hand, going into beeg Shaddols. The fusion also props their "going to grave" effects, extending your plays.  3x El Shaddol Fusion- El Shaddol Fusion is another fusion spell for the Shaddols, allowing you to go into more of the Shaddols, this time without having you summon one (unlike the equip). El is also a quick play, meaning you can fuse during either turn to interrupt your opponent's plays heavily.  Extra deck 2x Michael- Michale is fairly easy to go into, with a Raiden and another Lightsworn (most likely a Lumina, depending on your opening hand). Michael is great for non-destruction removal, as while it does target, it banishes, not destroys. Michael also allows you to recycle any number of Lightsworns into the deck from grave and gain a miniscule 300 LP for each, mills 3 during the end phase, and is a 26k beater. 2x Minerva- Minerva starts off with a simple effect of detaching a material to mill 3, which is great for propping the effects of Shaddols to extend your plays and make some fusions. And when Minerva is destroyed by battle or card effect, it mills 3 and destroys opponent's cards (without targeting) equal to the number of Lightsworns you milled with it, which can be great for blowing up the board so you can launch a comeback. Minerva is generally simple, but solid. 2x Curious- Curious is fairly hard to make, but can be completely worth it. On destruction, it bounces a card from your grave back to your hand, recycling resources.On summon, it sends any card from your deck to the grave, not just from the top, making Curious a foolish burial on legs. It also easily props the Shaddols without leaving it up to luck. Additionally, when a card is sent from the deck to the grave (whether it be by milling or by Curious' own Foolish burial), you can mill the top 3.  1x Shekhinga- Shekhinga is a negate on legs, which for this deck is great, as it doesn't have many negates. Shekhinga can negate special summoned monster effects by your opponent by sending Shaddol cards from your hand to the grave, which is actually a great cost, as it generates advantage for you by negating. Shekhinga also recovers Shaddol spells when sent to the grave. 1x Anoytalis- Anoytalis is more so a floodgate on legs, as it makes it so your opponent can't special summon monsters from hand or grave using spells/traps. This sounds oddly specific, but can be quite strong against some match ups. Like others, it recovers Shaddol spells/traps (i'm not going to always say this so this is your last time hearing my beautifal text line say it). 3x Construct- The main boss monster of the deck, Construct is fantastic. On summon, it fills up your grave with the Shaddols and activates their effects, extending your plays even more and filling up your grave. When Construct battles a Special Summoned monster, it destroys it without counting in battle damage, whcih is amazing since most boss monsters are special summoned.  1x Grysta- Grysta is a great negate on legs, as whenever your opponent would summon a monster, you can send a Shaddol card to negate the summon and destroy the monster. Like Shekinga, this is amazing, as it's a negate that generates you more advantage.  1x Wendigo- Wendigo is mainly here to wall up, but if i'm gonna be honest, also because I find her adorable. Not actually a very good card but too cute to pass up. 1x Winda- Winda is an amazing floodgate that's easy to summon in the deck, due to all the dark's. Each player can only summon one mosnter while she's face up, which, while it does hurt us, still is a great monster to drop on an end board so the opponent can barely do anything or has to dedicate resources to getting rid of it. 1x Alkapone- Alkapone allows you to basically permanently effect veiler a card, negating it's effects for the rest of the game, which is great for outing problem cards like Appolousa. It also has battle protection (which isn't super important but makes it annoying to deal with), and when it's sent to grave, it allows you to add any Shaddol card from deck to hand, then discard a card. Deck guide The deck's main strategy is to go first, mill a ton of cards, and set up an endboard of some fusions/synchros/ whatever you can get out.You'll want to Summon your main mill cards like Raiden, whether it be normal summoning them or summoning them off of Lumina. Afterwards, you should mill a ton to activate Shaddol effects and search and the such, allowing you to refill your hand, summon more monsters, etc. Then you can go into a Michael, Curious, etc, and then fuse your remaining Shaddols into a fusion. Afterwards, the deck just gets really grindy and just mills until it decks out or beats the shit out of the opponent with the big extra deck monsters.  (Things to note: This is mainly a going first deck, and Mystic Mine is a good option to replace Desires with in some match ups.)  Any suggestions or advice is appreciated, as always. Have a good day!

deck_excerpt: An Obelisk The Tormentor deck that uses tokens and special summons to have a lvl-deckbalance together with the high-lvl-monster cards, it works with
deck_description: Monsters: Obelisk the Tormentor – A great divine-beast card with 4000 atk, to summon it you need alot of Token and special summons, then you can use the normal summon to summon Obelisk, Metal Reflect Slime that turned to Egyptian God Slime is the alternative, but it's not needed and already strong as a stall card that has to be targeted. With Lair of Darkness you can tribute 2 opponent monsters and get 2 Torment-Token on your side which is really strong, but the effect has to destroy, so the opponent must have 3 monsters, otherwise you must tribute Obelisk or one of your monsters, because one target has to be left on the opponent's side for the effect. Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon – It can destroy a monster and it can special summon monsters in defensive Position from the hand or the graveyard when it destroys a monster in battle, good targets are Lightpulsar Dragon, Dragun Of Red-Eyes and Egyptian God Slime. Red-Eyes Black Dragon, Dark Magician – They must be in the deck for Red-Eyes Fusion to work, it won't work without both of the fusion materials as normal-monsters in the deck. This means it is always the first goal to summon a Dragun Of Red-Eyes, this way you don't have the 2 normal monsters in the deck anymore and your draw-phase becomes stronger, before that you have a little disadvantage if you draw one of them, but it's very easy to get 2 effect monsters on the field, even if you have both in the hand. With 2 effect monsters you get Predaplant Verte Anaconda and then you get Red-Eyes Fusion. This gives the deck also a burst-theme of strategy. Lightpulsar Dragon- can be special summoned with banishing one light and dark monster from the GY, and when it got send to the GY it can special summon a lvl 5 or higher Dark Dragon monster from the GY which are Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon, Red-Eyes Black Dragon and Vice Dragon. Vice Dragon – good special summon if you have no monsters. Black Dragon Collapserpent, White Dragon Wyverburster – With Obelisk the Tormentor, and the Dark cards, the deck is already a Light and Dark deck, that works good with Light-and-dark Special summons. Overflow Dragon – It is a level-1 Target for One for One, and a Dragon-target for Guardragon Elpy to special summon a dragon from the deck, or as a fusion with The Dark - Hex-Sealed Fusion to get a Dragun Of Red-Eyes. It gan be special summond from the deck and also summon tokens with Torrential Tribute, Link Burst and the monster-destroy-effects. Summoner Monk – If you use the effect you have 2 effect monster to summon Predaplant Verte Anaconda and get Dragun Of Red-Eyes. A good Target is Cyberse Gadget, but you can also get Ahrima, the Wicked Warden when you have Lair of Darkness to tribute an opponent monster. Phantom Skyblaster, Cyberse Gadget, Chaos Valkyria, Ahrima, the Wicked Warden – good level 4 cards that can summon token or that can special summoned, Ahrima, the Wicked Warden has a tribute effect for Lair of Darkness or can get it to the hand, Cyberse Gadget can summon a level 1 monster from the GY and is also a Cyberse monster, so you can also link-summon Clock Lizard with it. The Dark - Hex-Sealed Fusion – you can fusion summon Dragun of Red-eyes with it if you have one dragon-effect monster, the alternative is Predaplant Triphyoverutum with 3 dark-monsters. Scapeghost, Winged Kuriboh – Good Token-cards, Scapeghost is good with negations in general and also with Supply Squad, because even when it gets destroyed you can draw a card, and Winged Kuriboh is good with The Flute of Summoning Kuriboh which is a better One for One. It is also a light-monster and you can summon Linkuriboh to have a Light and a Dark monster in the GY when you use Linkuriboh further for other summons.   Extra Deck: Link: Linkuriboh, Link Spider: To use the tokens of Scapegoat, Scapeghost, Phantom Skyblaster and Lair of Darkness, they are also good for Link Burst and for Knightmare Phoenix to link it. Linkuriboh's GY-effect can bring him back for another token and also works with Lair of Darkness, so you can maybe tribute an opponents level-1 monster then. Guardragon Elpy: You can summon a Dragon from the deck whenever you have a dragon to link-summon it and two Cyberse-monsters (Linkuriboh, Link Spider, Cyberse Gadget, cyberse-Gadget-Token) to summon Clock Lizard, then you can summon Guardragon in the middleso that both Link monsters point to the left zone of Clock Lizard, it also works with Borrelguard Dragon as an alternative. Predaplant Verte Anaconda: It can be used as the first card to play with 2 effect monsters to get Dragun Of Red-Eyes as fast as possible, and to have the normal monsters in the deck in the GY. It can use Red-Eyes Fusion, Instant Fusion (without extra-costs) and Super Polymerization (without discard) as an effect for 2000lp. Beat Cop From The Underworld: it has a tribute effect as a link monster for Lair of Darkness to tribute an opponent's monsters, and it can protect monsters from Torrential Tribute or other cards. Clock Lizard: It can be used for Guardragon Elpy and also to get Fusion monsters back if you have the fusion monster and also the material in the GY. Knightmare Phoenix: a good backup card to detroy spell/traps and draw a card. Draco Masters Of The Tenyi: It is a cheap link-3 card if you have Linkuriboh together with Knightmare Phoenix, it cannot be destroyed by battle, and it can destroy monsters if you have tokens or normal monsters on the field or in the GY and no other effect monsters. Black Luster Soldier - Soldier Of Chaos: A good Link-3 Card that can banish cards or get a 4500atk monster, which is both great to make use out of the tokens or the special summons, with a level 7 or higher monster as material it also gets a good immunity. Borrelguard Dragon: a good link-4 monster, it cannot be destroyed by card effects, which means you can use Torrential Tribute as a very good combo, it also has a good defensive effect and it can summon monsters that got destroyed with negated effects for discarding a spell/trap card if it is useful. Fusion: Thousand-Eyes Restrict: a good target for Instant Fusion to steal an opponent's monster, and to summon Linkuriboh then to make use out of it and use it for other Link-monsters. Egyptian God Slime: A good stall monster that has to be targeted and attacked when you summon it from Metal Reflect Slime, it can be also used as a tribute to summon Obelisk the Tormenter if it is worth it. Dragun Of Red-Eyes: It is easy to summon it as the first monster with Predaplant Verte Anaconda that can be summoned from 2 effect monsters. You can also use The Dark - Hex-Sealed Fusion and a dragon-effect monster or one of the normal-monster materials. It can, like Borrelguard Dragon, also not be destroyed and it can not be targeted, so both are good combo's with Torrential Tribute. Predaplant Triphyoverutum: It is a target for Super Polymerization to tribute up to 3 of the opponent's monster and get a good summon-negate with it. You can use Lair of Darkness or Predaplant Verte Anaconda to turn the opponent monsters to dark monsters. Spells: Supply Squad, Link Burst, Pot of Duality, Pot of Disparity – A Draw engine that works very good with tokens, you can Link burst Linkuriboh and get it back with it's GY effect for another token. Pot of Duality and Pot of Disparity are the best support cards, but you can not special summon in the turn you activate Pot of Duality. For Pot of Disparity you can banish part of the link engine and fusion monsters: Link Spider, Guardragon Elpy, Beat Cop From the Underworld, Clock Lizard, Draco Masters Of The Tenyi, 1 Dragun of Red-Eyes. Lair of Darkness, Super Polymerization: Super Polymerization is a strong-effect-counter to tribute up to 3 monsters from the opponent if they are turned Dark with Lair of Darkness or Predaplant Verte Anaconda, then you also get Predaplant Triphyoverutum, if you have Lair of Darkness and no tribute effect you can use Beat Cop From the Underworld as a link-2 monster. Swords of Revealing Light, Red-Eyes Fusion: good stall for the tokens and special summons, and the fusion for Dragun of Red-Eyes. The Flute of Summoning Kuriboh, Scapegoat, Monster Reborn, Instant Fusion, One for One – Support cards for more tokens and special summons. Traps: Torrential Tribute – The best trap to clear the field with one card, the goal is to get Borrelguard Dragon or Dragun of Red-Eyes to have a monster that cannot be destroyed when you activate the card, if you don't have these, you can use it to draw cards with Supply Squad, or to counter the opponent when you got no monsters on the field. Metal Reflect Slime, Call of The Haunted – good stall and special summon cards, Metal Reflect Slime can be turned to Egyptian God Slime or to Link-summon Black Luster Soldier - Soldier Of Chaos, so opponents card effects cannot target it, because it is summoned with a level 7 or higher monster as material. Lost Wind – good negation, that can be used twice.

deck_name: Eldlich Sacred Beasts- Post Dec 2020 Banlist
deck_excerpt: Sacred Beasts, with an Eldlich engine for extra beatdown (yes i know) and some stun elements.
deck_description: So, here's another deck that doesn't need (or want) the Eldlich engine, but i'm mashing the Eldlich engine into it anyway, because my parents didn't love me enough as a child. This is basically Eldlich beatdown with Sacred Beast beatdown, so they hit really hard and either A) End the game in one turn, or B) Die to mirror force. So basically just the egyptian gods but actually good cards lol. Wish the Wicked Gods got more support tho Deck guide 2x Hamon- SODO NO CHI SADAMEEEEEE- Me being a dumbass aside, here we have Hamon, one of the two Sacred Beasts we're running (Uria was excluded due to a lack of traps). Hamon isn't too hard to get out due to Cerulean Skyfire, Opening, Eldland, etc. Cerulean Skyfire makes it easier to get out by using facedown spells, so you can use useless shit like Black Awakening for it. Hamon, on field, is a fairly solid beater in attack position that can do an extra 1000 burn damage whenever it attacks, which helps with an OTK. In defense, only he can be targeted for an attack, which is fine for walling up. Skyfire regularly changes it's position for negations, so it's not too hard to get both position effects off. 2x Raviel- Raviel was originally fairly hard to get out, but now it's actually pretty easy to get out. You can cheat out Raviel with Beast, getting it out onto the field much easier than how it'd normally be. Raviel requires 3 fiends to get out, so if you don't cheat it out, you can shit out a good amount of Fiends with stuff like Chupacabra and Dark Beckoning Beast. While Raviel is on the field, when the opponent normal summons, he gets a token. Said Token can be tributed for Raviel to gain the attack of the token (1000) as long as it lives through the opponent's turn. Raviel's secondary effect is that he can tribute other monsters to gain their attack, so you can tribute smaller and more useless monsters to copy  their attack for an OTK. 2x Shimmering Scraper- Shimmering Scraper is a great card for more Raviel focused builds, which this is in some part. Shimmering Scraper can actually be summoned onto by tributing any 3 monsters to special summon him, making him just a 4k beater for whenever you need him, but that's not the intended usage. The intended usage is to discard it and target Raviel to double it's attack, which combined with Raviel's attack gaining effect, can go to 8000 plus. And in the grave, he can tribute a monster to bounce himself back to the hand, being easily recycable. 3x Dark Beckoning Beast- Dark Beckoning Beast searches out all the Sacred Beasts or one of the cards that specifically mention it (which there are a lot of) to fill in the gaps in your hand and supply whichever Sacred Beast you need at the time. It also gives you an extra normal summon off a fiend with 0 attack/defense (AKA chaos summoning beast), making him a great extender for a lot of plays. 3x Chaos Summoning Beast- Chaos Summoning Beasts helps get out all the Sacred Beasts you need, as the deck searches heavily, meaning you can get both Hamon and Raviel to hand. You can cheat out the one you struggle to get out legitametly (most likely Raviel) and then send continous spells to summon Hamon, making a strong board of beaters that you can rank into Gustav later. 2x Eldlich- Eldlich fucking beatdown. This is a mistake of an idea, but later. Like i've said before, you want to quickly get out Eldlich as fast as possible by using his effect on things like Cursed Eldland for it's search. Eldlich, on field, is a 25k beater (yes I said it) to contribute to the OTK, and the other cards that stun the opponent center around Eldlich. 3x Chupacabra- Chupacabra provides Fiend field presence, allowing you to get a good amount of Field's onto the board so you can get Raviel out how it's supposed to and cheat out the Joseph Joestar Headass. It's discard can be pretty risky, but as long as you get lucky you can dump some stuff you'd want in the grave into the grave (like the Golden Land stuff) for their effects, and get the draw. Although, Chupacabra's discard effect is useless, so. 3x Cerulean Skyfire- Cerulean has a host of solid effects for the deck, and Hamon.  It's first effect allows you to use face down spells (regardless of type) for Hamon's summon, which is great for using dead cards like Eldlixer. It's second effect allows you to negate any spell/trap the opponent activates and change your Hamon to defense, and this is amazing for being treated as a passive effect, meaning it can actually negate spell speed 4 stuff like super poly. And whenever one of the Beasts leaves the field, you take no damage for the rest of the turnt hey left, preventing you getting OTKed yourself. 3x Spirit Gates- Spirit Gates searches out all of the Sacred Beasts, or any of the smaller support monsters, giving you literally anything you need for your Sacred Beast plays. Additionally, Spirit Gates allows you to discard a card to special a Fiend with 0 attack/defense from grave, which is fantastic. Personally, I like getting a field of 3 fiends (Chaos, Beckoning, and Chupacabra most likely), and then sending them all off for Raviel.  Then you activate Spirit Gates to bring Chaos back and use it's effect to bring back Chaos, tributing Chaos to special out Hamon and have a huge board of Sacred Beasts. And, if you  control a Level 10 monster, you can bounce back a continuas spell from grave to hand, allowing you to recycle all the cards you sent away for Hamon. 3x Fallen Paradise- Fallen Paradise gives great protection to all of the Sacred Beasts, so you won't put resources into them and then have them be immediately destroyed. Fallen Paradise also gives you an amazing draw 2 as long as you control 1 of the sacred beasts, allowing you to extend your plays. 3x Cursed Eldland- Cursed Eldland, at  a miniscule life point cost, searches out Eldlich and the golden land traps, filling in the gaps of your hand. You mainly want to search Eldlich, and then summon Eldlich by sending Cursed Eldland for Cursed Eldland's effect. When Cursed Eldland leaves the field, it sends an Eldlich monster or a Golden Land card from your deck to the grave, allowing you a ton of good graveyard set up for more plays. 1x Eldlixer- Eldlixer helps with swarming the field with multiple Eldliches, for Eldlich Beatdown or to overlay into a Gustav. Additionally, you can banish Eldlixer from the grave to set a Golden Land trap directly from deck to S/T. The second effect is the one you want most, which is why you mainly want to send Eldlixer off of Cursed Eldland or something in that vein. 3x Awakening- Awakening is basically a one-sided Skill Drain, and is an amazing card. As long as you control 1 Sacrd Beast, you gain LP whenever your opponent summons, equal to the attack of the summoned monster. This effect isn't very major, as gaining life points sucks. 2 is where it gets great; As long as you control 2 Sacred Beasts, which you want to, you negate the effects of all face up monsters the opponent controls. This cripples most modern strategies and is a one-sided Skill Drain, being an amazing effect. I won't even mention the 3 effect, because it's impossible to get. 3x Scarlet Sanguine- Scarlet Sanguine also allows you to get out Eldlich, helping a fair amount with swarming with the Golden Boys. Sanguine also helps you easily get out tons more of the Golden Land traps, as you can banish it from the grave to set one directly from deck. While you can only activate one of these effects per turn, making it a bit slow, it's still a solid card. 2x Conquistador- Conquistador helps a lot with removing problem cards, as it gives non-targeting removal, which is very powerful in the modern game. Conquistador helps a lot with clearing boards to pave the way for an OTK, and is also just a body on field for a Knightmare or something.  He can also be banished to set Eldlixer traps directly from deck, which is great. And, like Sanguine, only one effect can be activated per turn. 2x Golden Land Forever!- Forever is a great source of negates and such, as this deck lacks many negates outside of Skyfire. It can negate literally anything by tributing an Eldlich, which is a great effect for making sure the opponent can't launch a comeback and you can finish them off, if you didn't end the game in turn 1. The extra deck 3x Gustav Max- Gustav Max is a great rank 10 XYZ, as it allows you to finish off games with ease. You can go into it easily with stuff like Eldlich, since they swarm the field so much, and any of the Sacred Beasts you don't need. Once you get your opponent to a low LP total, you can use Gustav to finish them off, or to bring them to the brink of death. It's also a generally solid 3k beater. 3x Almiraj- Almiraj is mainly just Extra deck filler, although you can go into it sometimes if you bricked or something. 3x Borrelsword- Borrelsword is generally a great beater, and fits a lot into the OTK play style. If you have any left over monsters, you  can go into a Borrelsword to clear the opponent's field and do huge amounts of damage. 3x Pheonix- Pheonix allows you to clear problem backrow with any left over monsters, in case your opponent has something annoying up that you need to get rid of. 3x Unicorn- Unicorn is great for non-destruction removal, which is great in the modern game. It can clear the opponent's field and make it easy for an OTK. Playing Guide This deck is mainly a going second beatdown deck, which aims to close the game off in the first turn but has the Golden Land traps and such as insurance in case it doesn't. You want to lead off with activating Opening if you have it, to search and such, and also activating Fallen Paradise if you have it. Afterwards, you'll want to summon out Dark Beckoning alongside Chaos Beckoning. If you have a backrow that can manage 3 or more Continuous Spells, you'll want to tribute Chaos for Raviel, so you can get out Raviel easily and then get out Hamon legitametly. If you have Chupacabra in hand, you can summon it and get out 3 Fiends, to tribute for Raviel. Then you recycle Chaos with Opening, so you can get out Hamon illegitametly. Then, you'll have a field of both Sacred Beasts without much trouble. For the Eldlich, like normal, you'll want to activate Cursed Eldland to get Eldlich. Then, with Eldlich, you'll summon it by sending Eldland and then build up your backrow of strong Golden Land traps. From there, you want to mercillesly beat the shit out of the opponent. If they're not dead in turn 1, you want to stun them with the Golden Land traps so they can't do anything, and then finish them off in turn 2. Any suggestions or advice is appreciated. Thank you!

deck_excerpt: I love Legacy of Darkness for two reasons -- Warriors and Dragons! This time around, I got a metric butt-load of dragons (even if I didn't get Tyrant
deck_description:
What is a Boxing League?

A relatively new concept in TCG/CCG circles, a Boxing League involves taking a box of your choice and building a 40 card deck -- It's that simple to begin (and even simpler thanks to resources like the YGOPRO virtual pack opener!). The league aspect comes in after the first game, when you can then take a number of packs (usually 6) from another set and opening those to supplement your existing deck, so as you and your friends continue to play against each other, the decks evolve beyond just a set, sealed casual deck. You can apply any number of house rules to your own league; In this deck's case, I restricted myself to only Pre-GX era sets and allowed myself a Polymerization (having a small pool of universally available cards like Poly is helpful, you might want to consider cards like Premature Burial, Monster Reborn, Pot of Greed as one-offs etc. as a way of keeping things exciting and fast-paced).

deck_excerpt: Using Cyber Angels with support from Drytrons, that means all Cyber Angels and not just Benten.
deck_description: This deck uses the typical Drytron and Benten strategy of using Drytrons to tribute Benten to gain more advantage, but with also using the other Cyber Angel ritual monsters. The other Cyber Angel monsters have synergy with Benten whether it be using their effects by interacting with Cyber Angels in the graveyard or with Benten being able to search any Cyber Angel from the deck after being tributed, which is super easy with Drytrons. The main strategy is getting either Vrash, Izana or Dakini onto the field to cause some serious damage and if all else fails use the Extra Deck to summon strong monsters like Soldier of Chaos, Accesscode Talker, or Divine Arsenal AA Zeus.  This deck was built off of this decklist before I made some adjustments to it: https://ygoprodeck.com/drytrons-toolbox/  I recommend checking it out. I just thought I could make a more pure Cyber Angel deck with Drytron support since the Cyber Angels have some more synergy with each other.

deck_excerpt: Fossil Adamancipator deck, feat. Flint Cragger  (Also, some criticism of this deck would be nice! It's my first Fossil deck, and I wanna make better
deck_description: Fossil is an archetype I've been meaning to touch upon for a few months, but because I'm a lazy fool, it took me until almost Christmas 2020 to make a deck! For those of you who loved Nintendo's games, or have an autism-induced obsession with prehistoric life, this deck was named after the Fossil Fighters franchise. I actually got the first game when I was in my pre-teens, and I would play that crap for hours. HOURS spent digging up bones (and some fossilized droppings), cleaning them, and just slapping together teams of superpowered dinos. I also got Fossil Fighters: Champions, which was also a great game I got hooked on!     Anyways, this Fossil deck also uses a small Adamancipator engine, and for good reason. One of Fossil's newest support cards was Flint Cragger, which lets you discard a card and send one of their Fusion monsters from your Extra Deck to the Graveyard. And because most of them have Graveyard effects that either add cards to your hand or pop your opponent's card, losing that card in your hand isn't a big deal. So Flint Cragger works amazingly with the "Adamancipator" Tuners, since they can summon Rock non-Tuners from your deck.     Because Fossil is basically the Rock equivalent of Cyber Dragons, this deck has to go second every single time. With 9 hand traps, 2 Lightning Storm, and Harpie's Feather Duster, stopping your opponent from making any significant plays is top priority. Then on your turn, your goal is to try and get Fossil Fusion to your hand and OTK your opponent! And because Konami is too stupid to ban Halqifibrax, you can use Cross-Sheep to link climb into it, then use Halq's effect to go into Selene, and finally Accesscode Talker.     But if you need to go first, there is some hope for you. Due to Halq and Cross-Sheep making great extenders, you can use them going first to put two Link 2s on board, and use them to make Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. But because the Extra Deck is so tight, I couldn't put Masquerena in there. Ugh...

deck_excerpt: Time To Protest Against the King For His Tyrant Ways Down With The King! Down With The King!
deck_description: Having Fun

Introduction: Main Level Monsters:3,4; Main Summons: From the Deck ||Extra Summons: Xyz and Link Key cards: Madolche Anjelly, Madolche Petingcesseur, Madolche Salon.

Difficulty to use: 4/5  ||  Dead Hands: 2/20

 
HOW TO PLAY
What does the deck want to do? The deck based on going 1st wants to set its own board of spells mainly, resist the opponent's turn, making 2 solid interruptions, so as to do otk in turn 3 with our restarts.  
CONSIDERATIONS

Important Archetype Cards:

Madolche Salone: It must be played with 3 copies, beacause is the main engine of the deck, which allows us not to die from a single hand trap. Exemple like Magileine + Anjelly or Anjelly + Hootcake. Also allow us to resist much better to cards like Droll, Gamma or Ogre and to continue the combo with bad hands like: 2x Messangelato or 2x Hootcake. Madolche Cruffsant: This card opens up a whole world to the deck, as well as being another starter, it works even better as an extender allowing us to have a +1 on the field. Thanks to this card we can do anti Droll/Lancea combo, and it also very important to fix or improve hands like Anjelly + Messangelato.
STAPLE AND SPICY TECH

Staple to use:

Gozen Match: Is simply the best floodgate to use in this deck, playing only earth attribute monsters doesn't hinder us in the least but gives problems to most of our opponents, also allowing us to play around cards like Nibiru. Is a card that can also be considered very well as going 2nd, and therefore played directly from main. In this meta I decided to play it only in the side deck, because so many decks now, have a way to take it out.

deck_name: Dragon Link NEW 1.5 Card Combo! ft. VFD POST Banlist
deck_description:
Hello and welcome to my Dragon link build! This is an updated version of my old build that I uploaded last week. The combo for the last build was a 3 card combo and was very conditional, but I have updated it into a 1.5 card combo! Dragon Link is not going anywhere anytime soon! It even ends on the same end board as the last combo! This new combo requires any of the starters and any of the extenders or Rokket Tracer in hand to achieve. I also made this build having 2 main goals - to minimize bricks and to make it consistent. This is my favorite deck of all time alongside thunder dragons (coincidentally also in this deck) and I have put a lot of effort into making the deck, combos, typing all this up and making my video so I really hope you enjoy it!   Full Combo = Starter + Extender or Rokket Tracer  OR Full combo = Romulus + Extender or Rokket Tracer   Full combo results in -   Hand rip 1 Look at opponent’s extra deck and banish 1 Banish top card of opponent’s deck Apollusa (2 negates) True King of All Calamities (free win)   It does not matter how you get to romulus, you just need to get to romulus, you can do it with all of the starters or you can even use 2 extenders or 1 extender and a normal summon to do so, it does not matter. If you can get to Romulus, you are good. There are many other ways to do the same combo, for example you can do starter + silverrokket or if you draw absorouter you can do it another way - the thing is if you can get romulus to the field and have 1 way to get another monster to the field, you have full combo.    This is obviously post december 2020 banlist and since linkross, buster lock and smoke grenade got banned, this deck uses True King of all Calamities aka VFD as the main negate/win condition. This is a very consistent version of dragon link and you should be able to combo off very easily. To achieve this new combo I am utilizing the thunder dragons (dragondark and dragonroar). Dragonroar is not a brick it can be used with chaos space to achieve full combo (I show how to do this down below) but you NEVER want to see a dragondark in you hand EVER (No really drawing it is really bad).   If you want to learn how to do this new 1.5 card dragon link combo, I recommend you watch my youtube video - In it I explain all my card choices and also show the combo. Please subscribe to the channel and like the video it is a great way to support me and the channel. Also be sure to answer the poll question down below! Today’s poll question is: Imagine you are entering a HUGE Yugioh tournament, what deck would you use?   Link to the video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dmS1gtrr9ig   Card choices-  
Starters I am running 9 starters in this deck, 3 of all black metal dragon, chaos space (the best one) and Sefert. They are the cards that get your combo aka Romulus on your field and you will and want to see them in your hand all the time. If there is a case where you don’t see a starter in your hand, go into romulus using extenders! Getting any 2 dragons on the field = a starter and is a full combo! (with an extender or tracer)
Extenders I am running a lot of extenders since you will require them for the combo as well as to play through handtraps. The obvious ones are noctovision dragon, quick launch, world legacy gaurdragon and monster reborn. The not so obvious ones are - if your starter was black metal dragon then chaos space, white dragon and black dragon are extenders; if your starter was sefert then darkness metal dragon and chaos space (can search emperor) serve as extenders and if your starter was chaos space, darkness metal dragon and black metal dragon serve as extenders. Rokket tracer can be a replacement extender for the combo and also serves as an extender because it allows you to use Dragon Ravine to mill absorouter dragon and add another rokket to the hand so you can use boot and special summon 2 rokkets, and you don’t need an extra extender or it can even mill galactic spiral dragon which you can use to XYZ into Number 38 which is an extra negate!
Handtraps and Removal I am running 3 ash blossom, 3 gamma and 3 Imperm for the handtraps. I chose these specifically for a variety of reasons. Ash is one of the best handtraps in the game and can counter just about everything. Gamma in my opinion is the best handtrap of this format because it can counter VDF, It can protect you from getting hit with an ash when you tribute sefert or when you activate chaos space, when you use quick launch and some other cases as well. It also serves as a way to turbo out savage as soon as striker dragon hits the grave so that your combo can be nibiru proof. I am also running imperm because it is a solid handtrap in general and also because it cannot be negated with stuff like called by the grave. For removal I am running 3 cosmic cyclone, it is a solid card and can wreck backrow and mystic mine players. It is also a great counter to Virtual World, one of the top tier meta decks of this format since it gets rid of the trap gate which results in no target for the virtual world monsters to special summon themselves.
  Only 3 Bricks! (Cards you don’t want to see in your hand) -   There are only a few bricks in this deck. I count 3 real bricks. As I mentioned above, Thunder Dragondark is a brick, because you can’t do your combo if you draw it and it is a dead card in the hand. Another brick is PSY-frame Driver, but this is a brick I well worth playing because you need to to use gamma and gamma is the BEST handtrap in my opinion of this format. The last brick is Boot Sector Launch - it isn’t a dead card in hand or anything but you just don’t want to draw it because you are going to search it for free off of Striker dragon and nobody ashes a striker dragon (But there are always exceptions...). I have got this a lot saying absorouter dragon and galactic spiral dragon are bricks, here’s the thing - they are not, you can discard both of them from your hand and they are still useful and absorouter acts as an extra extender since it can special summon itself from the hand! Also drawing another rokket (not tracer) is also not that bad because you can summon itself and tracer from your hand for the combo, so you don’t need an extender! (That's why I said an extender or tracer because if you have tracer in hand you can mill absorouter using ravine add a rokket and then special summon both tracer and that rokket)   Going up against current meta and side deck choices -   The best meta decks of the format right now are Dinos, Virtual World, Zoodiac-Zeus, Drytron and just VFD in general. I have included counter measures in the main and side decks to deal with these. For dinos I am running 3 lancea to completely destroy them (are very dependent on banishing) and I am running 3 cosmic cyclone in the main deck to get rid of the lost world. To deal with Virtual world I am running 3 cosmic cyclone in the main deck to get rid of the traps gate they need to target to combo off and I am also running 3 Ice dragon’s Prison in the side deck to deal with the monsters they normal summon as targets for the Virtual World monsters. To deal with Zeus I am running the Dinowrestler and the Kaijus in the side deck. Finally to counter VFD I am running the gamma package in the main deck and I am also running forbidden droplet in the side deck (Kaiju and the Dinowrestler don’t counter VFD since its effect can be activated during the standby phase). I am also running a Harpie’s Feather Duster in the side deck to counter basically any backrow decks including Zoodiac and Eldlich. Nibiru is also in the side deck to counter basically any deck! You can main deck it if you want but I chose not to. If you really want you can also side Mask Of Restrict to counter Drytron, another meta contender. I have not been seeing too much Drytron so I decided to not side deck Mask of Restrict. Ice Dragon’s Prison, nibiru and ash blossom do a pretty good job dealing with Drytron and I wasn’t seeing too much Drytron so I figured that Mask of Restrict was not needed. You can side deck it if you are playing against a lot of Drytron, it is really your choice. You can side Dimensional Barrier to counter Drytron as well.    Changes you can make to the deck -    There are some changes you can definitely make to this deck, you don't have to but here are some things you can do! 
  1. Include the dragoon package- you are playing some extra bricks but you have extra deck space, you don’t need all the cards in there for the combo (you may want to play a 50 or 60 card deck if you want to include this)
  2. Add in more thunder dragon cards and/or add in thunder dragon fusion and titan - you can do this as well because in the combo after dragondark leaves the field you don’t search anything using its effect, you can utilize this opportunity to search something like Thunder dragon Fusion or Thunder Dragonhawk! (RIP Colossus we will remember you) I would go full 60 and add the dragoon package since verte can mill red-eyes fusion Thunder Dragon fusion and summon Titian and it can also mill red-eyes fusion and summon dragoon, it just works together better. You can even play 2 dragondark so drawing 1 won’t be the end of the world since you have another one in the main deck so you can do the combo
  3. Make it a 40 card deck - you can cut the handtraps/removal cards and the extenders down to a lower size and make it a 40 card deck, I felt like for consistency I need to make it 50 but 40 cards are also great!
  4. Make it a 60 card deck! (If this is one of your choices I like the way you are thinking!) - you should add in more extenders and removal cards if you are making it a 60 card deck, I would also put in the Dragoon package if I was going full 60 since there is a lower chance of drawing those bricks. If you are afraid to play the slow game you can also add a second boot sector launch and/or a second absorouter since you have space, in this case boot won’t be a brick since you are going to get another one via striker dragon to the hand anyway. 
  5. Main nibiru - the only reason I did not main Nibiru was because I was playing against dinos and Virtual World a lot and they both counter Nibiru very easily. Dinos use Miscell and Virtual World can make Number 75 before doing the VFD combo, it is your personal choice to do this or not.
  6. Side deck Ghost reaper and winter cherries - this is mainly to counter VFD and you can put it in if you wish, it does a great job against decks like virtual world, it can also get rid of dragoon if you choose to run it and it is also budget. It is an amazing pick because VFD is everywhere. You can also get rid of halq using reaper. The good thing about using reaper is that you will look at the opponent’s extra deck with Trish so you know what is in it, so depending on that you can add reaper from the side deck to the main deck depending on what the opponent is playing. I thought this was not needed but some people are even side decking zeus as a reaper target, this is ok if you have space. 
  Budget alternatives -    Not everyone can afford to buy every single card in this deck so I decided to throw in some budget alternatives as well. Dragon link is definitely not a budget deck but if you want to save some money here are some tips. The 1st one is handtraps, imperm is $30-40 and is not cheap, you can switch it out for anything cheaper - effect veiler is an awesome replacement and does the exact same thing. If you cannot afford ash blossom which is $7-8 a copy (maximum gold) you can replace it for something like ghost ogre. The handtrap you 100% need to play is gamma which is $1-2 a copy and is reasonably cheap. Gamma as I mentioned is the best handtrap of the format and you have to run it. Another non budget card I am running is Chaos Emperor Dragon which is $30-35 a copy - you could run like an extra lavineer but it is not the same since emperor is a +1 and it returns itself back to the bottom of the deck. Halq is another non budget card I am running which is about $30 a copy, sadly you have to get this card for this deck to work, there are no replacements. Forbidden droplet in the side deck can be replaced by Dark ruler no more but droplet is much better because it is quick play and counter VFD, dark ruler does the same thing except it is not quick play sadly. This is a little unfortunate and is all the more reason to run gamma. You can also put in ghost reaper and winter cherries as an alternative to get rid of VFD. You can also run the dragoon package if you have money, Dragoon’s price has gone down from $50 when it was released to $30 right now- of course it is not in this deck and is optional to add. You may be wondering why I only included these in the list, that’s because everything else is fairly cheap! Some that you may think are expensive are really not, you just need to buy the correct reprint. Some examples -   
  1. Apollusa ($3 maximum gold)
  2. Borrelsword ($3 maximum gold)
  3. Borreload savage ($7-8 Tin of lost memories)
  4. Unchained abomination ($1 tin of lost memories)
  5. Nibiru ($7-8 maximum gold)
  6. Striker dragon ($2-3 Tin of lost memories)
  Alternatives/Ratio change-   By alternatives what I mean is cards that you can put in if you are going for a larger deck or if you simply don’t like something in my deck or if you want to change up the ratios  
  • Starters some alternative starters are Chamber Dragonmaid and Parlor Dragonmaid paired with Dragonmaid Hospitality and Dragonmaid Tidying. You can normal summon chamber, search hospitality, link into striker, activate hospitality, bring back chamber and go into romulus (full combo with extender/any rokket) or you can normal parlor, mill tidying, link into striker, banish tidying to bring back parlor, and then link into romulus
  • Extenders some other extenders include Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm (Great paired up with chaos space and dragon shrine/foolish burial), Tempest the Dragon Ruler of Storms(can also be banished off of trishula to search crusadia draco and milled with dragon shrine to get itself back), Crusaida Draco (tempest can search), the Dragunity Phalynx/Dragunity lance package, unexpected dai paired with flamevell guard and galaxy serpent (this makes it so you don’t have to play the 1 rokket synchron, halq can just summon serpent/guard), dragon shrine, foolish burial, one for one, more absorouter dragons and so many more 
  • Handtraps/Removal You can play some alternatives for handtraps but please run gamma it is essential if you want to win. Some alternatives are nibiru, ghost ogre, veiler and even skull mister. For removal some alternatives are lightning storm, twin twisters and alpha the king of all beasts. You can also add knightmare Phoenix/knightmare unicorn replacing unchained abomination and/or heraldic seal - you don’t need those for the combos
    Typical end board -    The typical end board should be VFD, Apollusa and a Number 38 and/or a Borreload Savage Dragon. But always, there are exceptions. If your board gets hit by a nibiru or something a typical endboard would be a Borreload Savage and/or number 38 at the very least and can also include something like a heraldic seal. The deck is good at comboing with less resources and is also good at setting up multiple negate boards including VDF which I also like to call a free win. When going second a well established board may include VFD, Apollusa and something to finish the opponent off like borrelsword dragon or unchained abomination. In general Dragon Link is a solid deck and can do a lot of amazing combos but everything comes down to practice and how well you know to play this deck! Practise makes perfect! But all I can say is the deck is not going anywhere anytime soon!    How to combo if you draw Dragonroar (ss = Special Summon) -   
  1. activate chaos space, discard dragonroar, add white dragon 
  2. Banish dragon roar to ss white dragon
  3. Dragonroar effect, ss dragondark from deck
  4. Go into striker dragon and romulus doing the combo like usual
  After this you just do the same combo as the one in the video, just pretend the dragondark isn’t there and you can banish whatever you want with trish, if you are going full 60 you can banish tempest and add crusadia draco to your hand! This will be an extra extender you can use to go into savage/number 38 if you have spiral.   Final tips -   Some tips/mistakes I see a lot of players make while playing this deck. Put your negates in defense mode  - it is very important to put your negates in defense mode when possible (links are an exception) mainly cards like VFD, number 38 and Borreload savage, putting them in attack mode is a risk and if your opponent lightning storms you, you must waste that savage negate/number 38 negate and in the case of VFD, if you need to stall out a little longer you can even use its effect on the opponent’s next turn but if you get hit with lightning storm because VFD was in attack,  well you can’t do that anymore. There was a point when my savage dragon had 4500 attack but still I put it in defense because the negate is what matters, you can kill your opponent on the following turn. Another common mistake is people not making savage/apollusa as soon as possible - nibiru still beats this deck and it is important to make these before you get hit hard. For example as soon as you have something like gamma/driver I like to make a savage as soon as striker dragon hits the graveyard. Keep those in mind while playing this deck!   Conclusion -    Again, if you want to learn how to do this new 1.5 card dragon link combo, I recommend you watch my youtube video - In it I explain all my card choices and it  shows the combo as well. Overall Dragon Link is still a solid deck and the Banlist changed very little of how good the deck is. It does change the combos and the endboard and all but it doesn't change how the deck is played overall. If you play this deck more and practise I am sure you will get better at playing this deck and you will start winning duels! Practise makes perfect. Let’s take Dragon Link to the next level! Hope you have fun playing and messing around with this deck! Let me know your thoughts about the poll question down below!   Link to the video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dmS1gtrr9ig   Thanks and I will see you next time! :D

deck_excerpt: Zoodiac Eldlich deck December 2020  (Also, a recommendation for an entertaining AND EDUCATIONAL YouTube channel in the description!)
deck_description: This is a Zoodiac Eldlich deck I build earlier today, inspired by Overly Sarcastic Productions, a pair of college-age YouTubers who make content focusing on fiction and history. One of their video series was on "Journey to The West", a 16th-century Diet Japanese (I refuse to call China by its real name; they know what they did) novel that focuses heavily on Sun Wukong, the Monkey King. Given how the Zoodiacs are based on the Diet Japanese Zodiac, and how the mythical El Dorado is located in South America below the Equator, "Journey To The South" is an appropriate name for the deck.   For anyone who wants to watch the "Journey To The West" video series, feel free to click this link!  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=61nuXrvqNgI&list=PLDb22nlVXGgdg_NR_-GtTrMnbMVmtSSXa   If you want to check out Overly Sarcastic Productions' channel in general, click the link here! https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCodbH5mUeF-m_BsNueRDjcw   While the deck does have a total of 9 hand traps (12 if the Side Deck is included), going first is ideal because of the numerous Traps in it. Due to how the Zoodiac Xyz monsters can be summoned, and Boarbow's ability to attack directly, going second can result in you summoning a 6-material AA-ZEUS without activating a single card. The side deck is full of "go-second" cards, in case you need to play a more aggressive version of Zoodiacs.

deck_excerpt: Amorphage Goliath lock with Hope Harbinger and Blue Eyes Spirit Dragon
deck_description: The goal of this deck is to, at the very least, get out Seals, Spirit Dragon and Hope Harbinger with Goliath as the Seals summon target. Hope Harbinger provides battle protection for Goliath while Azure Eyes tagged out from Spirit Dragon provides great effect protection. Timing is important for this as you want to tag out Spirit Dragon when Seals activates its special summon effect after it's been tributed, not when you uses it's bounce effect. Otherwise Goliath wont get protection.  Seyfert and Chaos Space are important as they get you your baby chaos dragons which are, more often than not, necessary. Your good extenders include Noctovision, White Rose and Draco as they're all free special summons. It's also very important to have the Stone of Legend specifically in the GY. Spiral Dragon and/or tempest usually come out at the end of your combo for your last rank 8 which should be Photon Lord most of the time.
