deck_excerpt: End your turn with a protected Sacred Beast and a powered up Dragoon
deck_description: This deck is super easy, the goal is to draw either Opening of the Spirit Gates and/or Dark Beckoning Beast. You'll use either one of those to search Chaos Summoning Beast and the other to search Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder. Use Chaos to summon Hamon in defense then use Opening of the Spirit Gates to bring back Chaos then link off Dark Beckoning and Chaos for Predaplant Verte Anaconda so that you can bring out Dragoon. Use Chaos' graveyard effect to get you Fallen Paradise, use Fallen Paradise to protect Hamon and to draw two more cards. Use Predaplant's effect to target Hamon but then use Dragoons effect to negate so that Predaplant gets destroyed and Dragoon gain 1000 ATK.

deck_excerpt: Extremly consistent True Draco deck with support from the Monarch Spells&Traps.
deck_description: The strategy of the deck is to set up a board with any True Draco monster + either The Monarchs Erupt (basically a better Skill Drain) or Domain of the True Monarchs(basically a Dragon Buster Destruction Sword -R.I.P.), which most of the decks of the current format can't deal with. Thanks to the Pantheism of the Monarchs and the other draw cards( Pot of Duality, Macicians Souls, True Draco Heritage, Card of Demise) its extremly consistent in doing this.  The deck is immune to almost every handtrap or floodgates(even V.F.D. and Vanities Ruler) and very well in the grind game, what makes it a perfect Anti-Meta strategy. Obviously you want to go first, but thanks to the True Draco Spells and Traps or cards like The Monarch Stormforth the deck does pretty well in breaking bords going 2nd, too.  Enjoy!

What is a Boxing League?

A relatively new concept in TCG/CCG circles, a Boxing League involves taking a box of your choice and building a 40 card deck -- It's that simple to begin (and even simpler thanks to resources like the YGOPRO virtual pack opener!). The league aspect comes in after the first game, when you can then take a number of packs (usually 6) from another set and opening those to supplement your existing deck, so as you and your friends continue to play against each other, the decks evolve beyond just a set, sealed casual deck. Big pulls from Galactic Overlord! A buttload of Hieratics, a good pool of XYZs including Neo-Eyes -- Generic big dragon beatdown! Nitwit Outwit works like a treat here too.

deck_excerpt: I bet you didnt know that Mekk-knights could make a 3 material VFD
deck_description:
Full Combo (VFD): Girsu+1 light mekk knight or tiamaton (would be a 1 card combo if linkross wasnt banned)
  1. Summon Girsu, use his eff to send world armor from the deck to the gy
  2. Use girsu eff to summon 2 tokens. put 1 in the opponent monster zone thats in front of the 2nd extra zone
  3. link your token and girsu for lib, put her in the extra monster zone in the column of the opponent token
  4. use lib eff to set succession form the deck in her column
  5. sp summon the mekk knight from your hand into libs column OR sp summon tiamaton to a zone that is NOT in libs column or zone she points to.
  6. flip succession to revive armor
  7. Armor eff to search monstrosity
  8. link away lib for gardna, use lib eff; target the opponent token
  9. tribute gardna, armor, and the mekk-knight/tiamaton for trishula
  10. Activate monstrosity, target trishula, sp summon thunder king and kaku
  11. Overlay for a VFD with 3 materials
Combo 2 (Ding): Girsu
  1. Summon girsu, use his eff to sent armor.
  2. use girsu eff to summon token
  3. Link the token away for linkuriboh

deck_excerpt: Virtual World deck December 2020  ("NTR" because Calamities cucks your opponent out of playing YGO!)
deck_description: It took me a while, but I finally made a Calamities Turbo--I mean Virtual World--deck! Anyone who's read manga knows what NTR really means. As for why I called this deck "Neo Tokyo Rave!", it's because some of the Virtual World monsters have Japanese words in their name, such as "hime", "roshi", and "kyubi." Also, I know that this deck has a Diet Japanese theme, but I still do not forgive Ch*na for giving us the Coronavirus.     *Sighs* Anyways, this deck uses a total of 9 hand traps, as well as 2 Lightning Storm and Harpie's Feather Duster. Despite this, the deck works beautifully going first, because it can easily end on a True King of All Calamities and a face-up Chuchi that can pop one of your opponent's cards. And if you don't have the necessary levels needed to summon Calamities--which for me personally was rare--Photon Strike Bounzer makes for an OK substitute.     Actually, now that I think about it, NTR is an appropriate name for this deck, because it cucks your opponent out of playing the game.

deck_excerpt: This is my deck Justin and he's taken but he's cracked at Yugioh my guy UHH
deck_description: This is the first deck I'm uploading - I've been pretty successful with it on dueling nexus, and ideally would love to construct a physical deck with it (would run about $200 total as of writing). Card explanations below... MAIN DECK Gizmek Kaku - This card is pretty underrated imo, as the extra zone is used in 95% of opponents decks and this card gives you a free special summon and equip (which bypasses cards that cannot be destroyed. Don't run more than 2 copies as if your opponent for some reason doesn't use the extra deck then it is basically a dead card (but again, who doesn't in 2o20 yugioh?) Radian (Kaiju) - Dark Kaiju + staple hand trap to remove tricky targets (Dragoon etc.) Hexe Trude - Special Summoned with Golden Castle of Stromberg, gives you a free pop and can be searched from deck (normal summon). Ash Blossom - 3 Copies NECESSARY in today's meta Necroface - The most important part of this deck, as for longer duels (more than 4-5 turns with this deck) it recycles your entire deck. Can make for easy otk with Forbidden Chalice if you have a lot of cards removed (or your opponent does) Gren Maju - OTK that has no protection so SAVE until board is wiped and you are sure your opponent has no attack stoppers Eater of Millions - Free 1 attack protection per turn, easy special summon, removes from play difficult monsters. Sometimes if you have 30+ cards removed this can also be a great beatstick if you don't need to immediately remove opponents monster from play Gizmek Orochi - Pesky, free 8 card banish, monster destruction, quick effect summon. Easily three copies Dimension Shifter - If you cross your fingers and are able to draw this first turn, it completely shuts down opponents graveyard. I'm not sure if i'd run this in every era with this deck, but with graveyard effects being SO prevalent in the meta, you'll want to run this bad boy. Dimensional Fissure - One per deck, must have for banished decks Harpie's Feather Duster - Staple Raigeki - Staple (can also be combo'd with Forbidden Chalice to block negate) Cosmic Cyclone - Staple Allure of Darkness - Great draw power + rarely have to worry about not having dark monsters in this deck Golden Castle of Stromberg - Perfect for this deck; it has battle protection, free 10 card banish, and allows you to search Hexe Trude from deck Pot of Desires - Also perfect for this deck; staple Macro Cosmos - Staple in banished decks D.D. Dynamite - Was hesitant to run this for a while but it is REALLY helpful. 10 cards in opponents banished zone (pot of desires, dimensional shifter, necroface banish effect etc.) gives you 3000 free damage, and when your opponent manages to build a strong board but you just need a little extra damage to finish off the game, this is the way to go. Can also be combo'd with soul release but imo dimension shifter is better. Evenly Matched - Staple Dogmatika Punishment - Staple + Combo with Elder Entity N'tss for 2 pops   SIDE DECK Galaxy Eyes Cipher Dragon - Combo for blade dragon Galaxy Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon - Good mp2 usage, can give you 3 pops and a special summon when destroyed to go BACK into another copy. Has helped me completely shut down opponent boards. Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus - Can go into with either galaxy eyes dragon for easy board control Starving Venom Fusion Dragon - Must have w/super poly Elder Entity N'tss - Combo with Dogmatika Punishment for an extra pop   EXTRA DECK Nibiru - Staple Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay - KILLER for link focused decks and also have built in negate. The only reason I don't run it in main deck is because if the opponent doesn't use link monsters, it's a dead card. System Down - Cyber Dragon killer Super Poly - Staple Twin Twisters - Mystic Mine + Eldlich killer (staple) Cosmic Cyclone - Staple

Draw, draw, and draw some more (and then save yourself from decking yourself out with avarice). The idea of this deck is to draw as many cards as possible. The main idea is to get as many cards in the graveyard as possible and get to one of your Beginning of the End. This is accomplished first through overlaying for Coach King Giantrainer and Dugares. If this cannot be accomplished, there are backup options to getting to a Beginning of the End through Curious and Saryuja. There several end boards which can give you a successful board lock going first. You want some sort of combination of Apollousa, Dweller, Hope Harbinger, Vanity's Ruler, Dingirsu, and Dark Rebellion XYZ Dragon (equipped with Dragon's Bind). If all else fails, slap down Bagooska.  Two Dingirsus allows you to several things. First, you can possibly play it turn one and turn two. Second, if you get into a grind game, it is nice to have a second Dingirsu send effect. Third, it allows you to go into Pain Gainer, which has an effect similar to raigeki. After you use Pain Gainer, you can go into Sevens Sins, the beefiest spider of them all. If you haven't used Dugares, you can use his other effect to double Seven Sins attack to 8000.  You can also play offense with Black Luster Soldier and Accesscode Talker.

deck_name: Cryptid's Quick Lists - Zoodiac Eldlich - December 21st Build
deck_excerpt: A short look at the meta-defining Zoodiac Eldlich deck build for the December 2020 meta-game with full combo guide and my thoughts on the current stat
deck_description:
Cryptid’s Quick Lists – Zoodiac Eldlich Dec 2020
  1. Introduction
  2. Combo Guide
  3. Final Thoughts
1. Introduction Before I get started I’d like to take a sec to plug my discord server The Yu-Gi-Oh Writer’s Guild. We’re a community of Yu-Gi-Oh players and content creators who host regular events and offer feedback on your lists or guides. We have a Tag-Duel Tourney coming up soon as well as more events coming early next year. If any of this interests you I’ll leave a link to the server here. It’s been a while since I released a guide as my larger projects are taking substantial time to complete and maintain. Due to this I decided to try a shorter format guide to share lists I’m working on or playing in events that don’t fit my normal style of guide. This guide format will focus more on the decks core lines and follow-up plays along with any observations I’ve made during testing or play. All that said we’ll begin this series with with my current ranked deck Zoodiac Eldlich. On its own Zoodiac has had a storied history of meta play leading to a ban on both Zoodiac Drident and Broadbull on the September 2017 banlist. Zoodiac Drident was released to one earlier this year and this along with the recent release of Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus Sky Thunder has propelled Zoodiac to Tier 1 again. Eldlich was likewise released earlier this year and in a similar arc to Zoodiac has featured in various decks between Tiers 1-3 since. The combination of the 2 has been spotted in top-cuts throughout 2020 although I was first exposed to it via Kyle Lemieux`s top 16 list from PPG Weekend #4. My list features the standard line-up of Zoodiac monsters and a somewhat conservative Eldlich package to make room for tech choice such as the Artifact Scythe package and Imperial order. 2. Combo Guide A quick primer before I begin our look at the deck’s combos and follow-ups I’ve chosen these particular lines due to their frequency in my time with the deck. As with my other guides I’ll try to explain a variety of follow-up options for the hands however I always encourage ones own testing with any deck to fully understand the deck’s lines. 1) Any 1 Zoodiac Monster The first line we’ll be looking at is the deck’s most basic line for going first or second as it only requires one card. We begin by normal summoning our Zoodiac monster, for the purpose of this I’ll use Thoroughblade as an example. From there you’ll want to resolve any productive on-summon effects before overlaying Thoroughblade for Zoodiac Hammerkong. Your next choice depends on if you’re on the play or draw: if you’re on the play you’ll overlay Hammerkong into Zoodiac Drident, whereas if you’re on the draw you’ll want to overlay into Zoodiac Boarbow. Drident will give you at least a pop going first, if not more depending on which Zoodiac monsters are attached to her and what else you opened. On the other hand Zoodiac Boarbow enables Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus – Sky Thunder going second as potentially an OTK that turn depending on what else you opened. Conveniently AA-Zeus is also a suitable follow-up if you overlay an additional couple Zoodiac XYZ’s monsters during the line. Both of these lines are independently powerful as well as an excellent compliment to other forms of interaction like Imperial Order or Artifact Sanctum. 2) Zoodiac Ratpier Next up is the staple combo of 2020 Zoodiac decks: The Megaclops Combo. For those unaware Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops is an enormous link 3 requiring 3 XYZs monsters to summon, a trivial task for this list. While there are a number of lines that can end on Megaclops I’ve chosen to cover the most direct line. Starting from the summon of Zoodiac Ratpier we activate its effect to Foolish Zoodiac Ramram before overlaying into Zoodiac Hammerkong and Zoodiac Chakanine respectively. From there you’ll want to detach Hammerkong for Chakanine’s effect to summon Ramram from the graveyard before overlaying Chakanine into Zoodiac Drident. We then use Drident’s effect to destroy Ramram by detaching Chakanine before re-summoning Chakanine with Ramram’s graveyard effect. To finish the line all we have to do is overlay Zoodiac Drident into Zoodiac Tigermortar and use her effect (ideally by detaching Drident itself for extra set-up) to attach Ramram to Chakanine in order to fire her effect again to summon Hammerkong. Finally we’ll link all 3 XYZs into the titular Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops. On its own it represents a large and mostly immovable body however combined with any other interaction such as our Eldlich engine or Handtraps, Megaclops can spell a quick defeat for your opponent. 3) Cursed Eldland + Any Eldlich Spell/Trap + Zoodiac Ratpier The final line we'll be covering today is a hybrid, based on average end boards of both halves of the deck. To start we first normal summon Zoodiac Ratpier before activating its effect to foolish Zoodiac Ramram. From there we'll overlay into Zoodiacs Hammerkong and Chakanine before activating Chakanine's effect by detaching Hammerkong to summon Hammerkong from the graveyard. It's at this point that the Eldlich portion of the deck comes into play with Cursed Eldland. Use it search Eldlich the Golden Lord before discarding your Eldlich Spell/Trap of choice to send Cursed Eldland to the graveyard. From there we trigger it's effect to Foolish another relevant Edlich card, in this case I'll use Haquero of the Golden Land as an example. Next we set our Eldlich Spell/Trap and pop it so activate Eldlich the Golden Lord's resurrection effect. From here we can close the Eldlich half of the line by activating the grave effects of both Eldlich Spell/Traps we Foolished during the preceding plays. Finally to finish we'll overlay Zoodiac Chakanine into Zoodiac Tigermortar. We then use her effect to attach Zoodiac Ramram to Hammerkong before overlaying Chakanine into Zoodiac Drident. All together this board will optimally leave you with 2 pops and pseudo-Towers in the form of Eldlich the Golden Lord and Zoodiac Hammerkong, plus any other applicable interaction one opens. 3. Final Thoughts At the end of this guide I'd just like to thank everyone for reading this! Let me know what you think of the new format in the comments below or my server, link here. As the meta continues to evolve post the December 2020 Banlist one can expect a variety of changes to established strategies as well as a few newcomers in the form of decks like Draitron. However Zoodiac Eldlich seems to be evergreen in the current meta just as it has been all year. The deck’s power was raised somewhat with the addition of AA-Zeus but at its dual-archetype core the deck's lines are mostly unchanged from earlier builds. I've really enjoyed my time with the deck despite a lack of any meaningful competitive data due to its sheer versatility across a variety of openings. If I had to pick on one weakness of this build it would be its reliance on the normal summon sticking on the first turn in order to execute its powerful extradeck plays. One could perhaps remedy this with the addition of a card like Triple Tactics Talent although I don't think that will help versus more control oriented strategies. Overall Zoodiac Eldlich is a solid deck with some interesting interaction and several powerful pay-offs but is limited due to its reliance on the normal summon.

deck_excerpt: Lots of stuns negates, and OTK
deck_description: I recently got into the more annoying stun/control type decks, and I love both the Numeron and Eldlich engines, so I wanted to try and put together a deck that incorporated both, plus a lot of disruptions and negates. My ratio's for a few different cards aren't 100% decided, but so far it's performing pretty nicely. A couple of the one-of spells are in there just as backups, depending on if I bricked. Called By still comes in handy sometimes. Foolish Burial Goods to send one of my eldlich spells, to get the banish effect. Memories of hope, to get a free draw 4 (assuming it goes through). Right now Lightning Storm is sided because I haven't decided whether I can make use of main decking it. But generally this deck likes to go second. It can go first, it just won't be as strong, depending on what you draw. If I go turn 2, I love sending Eldlich to grave to bump to the grave opponents boss monster that they ended on, or spell or trap. Then the board is still free for me to start the Numeron engine. I love rogue decks the most, even if they aren't the best, and having fun is most important to me, so try it out if you're interested.

deck_description: OK, so in July 2020, I made a pure Tribrigade deck, but I was too lazy to finish testing it. But now that Tri-Brigade Kit and Bearbloom are a thing, I finally got around to making a deck profile. That lead me to making this masterpiece. I call it "Tri-Brigade Mirko the Lapin Legend", after My Hero Academia's best waifu, Mirko the Rabbit Hero("Lapin" is another word for "Rabbit")! It does make sense considering that the majority of the monsters are humanoid animals, and that almost all of the monsters are animalistic in general.   As for the deck's strategy, it can do well going first or second. First because the deck can either end on a Tri-Brigade Revolt or the Apex Avian/Thunderbird infinite negates loop. Second because the deck uses 9 hand traps, 2 Lightning Storm, and Harpie's Feather Duster. Cockadoodledoo is mainly there to go into Halqifibrax and link climb into Accesscode Talker if going second. As for the side deck, it uses 12 cards that can be used in the meta, and 3 Reborn Tengu because its floating effect makes it a good extender for Tri-Brigade.

deck_excerpt: Summon as many as 4 Synchro monsters in one turn!
deck_description: This deck is very simple. Either summon Hajun and use his ability to get Dakki, or summon Dakki and use Yuki-Musume's ability to summon Yuki-Musume. Once you have either of these, Synchro summon the Wheeled Mayakashi. You then use Dakki's ability to summon her back and you will find you can Synchro again. Keep up this process until you get the Skeletal Mayakashi. Then use Yuki-Musume's ability to summon her back, then send Mezuki to the Graveyard. Mezuki can summon any Graveyard monster back by banishing himself. This means if your Mayakashi monsters are beaten, you can summon them right back. You can also use Card Destruction to get a new hand if you need to. Now for Eldlich... Use Scarlet Sanguine to summon Eldlich. If Eldlich is defeated, you can discard 1 Spell/Trap, then get Eldlich back and summon him stronger than ever! If Scarlet Sanguine is destroyed, use it's effect and set the Conquistador. Then if the Conquistador is defeated, you can get another Scarlet Sanguine. Uni-Zombie is just there for bait or re-summons to my knowledge.

So, I saw the new Dogmatika Ritual, and wanted to try this out. I know next to nothing about Nekroz deck builds or Dogmatika builds, but I think that I got a pretty solid deck here. You wanna go first and stick Unicore, obvious statement is obvious. But the Dogmatika Ritual can send N'Tss or Herald or anything from the extra deck for some fun effects. The Dogmatika monsters in the Main Deck can also do some fun things. I've been having a lot of fun with the deck so far!

deck_name: Rokket Dragon Link Dec 2020 Post Banlist
deck_excerpt: Rokkets from 2019, but with all the modern bells and whistles.
deck_description: Rokkets go brrr. Okay, so Linkross is a big hit to the deck, basically losing a free extender out of the extra deck, and killing off MY pathways instead of normal (more successful?) Rokket players. HOWEVER, old paths are still possible, and many broken cards are still accessible to achieve the dream of comboing off to unbreakable boards.  I initially wanted to cut the deck back down to 40, but I found that wouldn't work with the number of cards I now considered essential. In the end, I settled on 49 cards - slightly bulkier than I could cut it to, but with good solid ratios and a reasonable amount of interaction for a combo deck.  In the second build, I increased the Red-Eyes engine. Having more bricks might seem bad, and Wyvern is not a good card, but since this combo path eats up cards and wants to end on Dragoon, I liked being able to add 2 cards to discard and potentially even one more to put back into the deck.  We still have all of our starters - 3 Seyfert, 3 Chaos Space, the Black and White Dragon, One for One , Black Metal Dragon, and REDM. That's 11 cards that either get you there, or get you there with another of your monsters, (over 1/5 of the 49 card deck) and Chaos Space is also a broken extender when you see it. The Rokket Package at this point is pretty standard, these are the essentials. One Brotaur still makes the cut to search your dragons, with Levianeer to search, but generally you almost always want to search your Black Metal Dragon. 1 each of Boot Sector Launch and Dragon Ravine, which are combo pieces and good cards, and 1 Divine Lance ance and 1 Dragunity Phalanx, for the option to make Needlefibre and generate value off of Plaguespreader Zombie, also just nice to have when you see Ravine. For extenders it is 3 Noctovision, which is straight busted, 3 Quick Launch which is honestly similarly busted, and 2 World Legacy Guardragon, alongside the 1 Monster Reborn. Quick Launch can actually start you, Noctovision extends you while drawing a free card, and World Legacy Guardragon can get you value in a grind game, or be popped by Tracer to preserve your field spell. The deck also plays through hand traps pretty well, since 2 dragons starts you nicely. Adding to this, the Dragoon Package is also in here. The idea was to be the 2019 Rokket deck, except with all the modern bells and whistles. Dragoon can be an insane back-up boss monster, in case you don't see enough extenders, or can help you end on the five negate board (which is still a 2 card combo even without Linkross, though you need a discard for Dragoon.) If you can trigger Black Metal Dragon multiple times in a turn, you can easily fuel the discard for this card. Lastly, for hand traps, I think 3 Ash Blossom and 3 Ghost Belle seems good for this current format, since both hit Virtual World and Eldlich reasonably well, while being generally useful interactive cards in a lot of other matchups, and then I took some backrow removal main, since it seems really good right now with Zoo and Eldlich playing together, as well as all of the Traps being worked into modern archetypes, including Virtual World. Traps are good right now, so I'm assuming hosing traps is good right now. Cosmic seems the spell of choice in the format, sensible with Eldlich and Virtual World both having GY effects on their traps.  I always like to bring Hand Traps in the side, so for this side I chose 3 Nibiru. These could honestly be main deckable, but it feels like people are prepared for it now, and modern combos are resilient enough that Nib often isn't enough anymore. Nonetheless, sometimes I'll need more hand traps, and Nib is the best bet that isn't Gamma (I just don't have room for the Driver). I also have 3 Lancea, which I like against Virtual World, and which works with the Dagda package in the extra deck. DRNM is our going second board breaking card - the deck has some board breaking and OTK potential, especially with Borrelsword Dragon still being relevant in this particular deck (sees some other niche play, but not much). Still, we're a going first combo deck, so some free "I win" cards in certain matchups are probably a good idea. We've got 2 Lightning Storm and a Harpie's Feather Duster for backrow, adding to the Cosmic pressure when going second - these are also helpful in breaking boards, but being flexible means I can slot these in the Spell/Trap removal slot while also breaking boards sometimes. D.D.G is our going first "skip your turn" flex cards - if you know you're going first, you can cheese out wins with these cards against most meta decks. These are more controlly cards, but I like having the option to play more control, particularly since we're now ending on slightly smaller boards of a few powerful negatey beatstickes. One of the main goals of the deck is to us up an opponent's negates and then make Dragoon to win.  Extra deck is every card needed to combo off into Savage + Abomination off of 1 card, plus Dragoon and Needlefibre, to generate as much easy value out of the extra deck as possible. There's also a Borrelsword Dragon in there to OTK going second, and Apollo, to set up even more negates going first.  Combos  Combo 1 - Seyfert, or any 2 Dragons on the field, including a level 4 or lower. This combo requires pitching 1 card as well.  1 - Summon Seyfert, eff, add Black Dragon  2 - Banish Seyfert, summon Black Dragon  3 - Link Black Dragon into Striker Dragon - chain links debateable, but add Boot Sector Launch and White Dragon  4 - Banish Black Dragon, summon White Dragon  5 - Link Striker + White Dragon into Romulus, add Dragon Ravine  6 - Dragon Ravine, discard 1, send Absorouter Dragon, add Tracer  7 - Boot Sector Launch, summon Tracer  8 - Tracer eff, destroy Boot Sector, summon Silverrokket (locked into DARKs out of the extra deck now)  9 - Link Silverrokket into Elpy, Tracer into Striker (momentarily locked into Dragons)  10 - Summon Black Metal Dragon (we are looking to abuse the everloving heck out of this thing not having a once per turn)  11 - Link Black Metal into Pisty, add Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon  12 - Banish Striker, summon REDM to the far corner.  13 - Pisty eff, summon Black Metal.  14 - REDM eff, summon Tracer  15 - Link Black Metal + Pisty into Quadborrel, add Red-Eyes Wyvern  16 - Link Pisty + Elpy into Dillingerous Dragon  17 - Quadborrel eff, targeting Dillingerous Dragon - end result is you summon back the Tracer, Siverrokket, and Dillingerous Dragon  18 - Make Borreload Savage  19 - Make Unchained Abomination  20 - Make Verte Anaconda  21 - Make Dragoon. Is this Red-Eyes?? ;)  22 - Abomination eff, pop Verte Anaconda. It has done its job  So, that's 3 discards total - 1 for Ravine that you can't get around in this route, 1 for Quadborrel that the combo fuels, and 1 for Dragoon on your opponent's turn. In exchange you get 2 omni-negates, one which destroys, and a thing that pops cards when your negate destroys and during the end phase (not to mention during the Battle Phase is something is beat over). However, with a single extender you can mitigate the first discard and make Apollousa before you summon Elpy, making the combo both more powerful and harder to interrupt. At its very peak the deck can simultaneously draw and search a lot of cards in its combos to fuel the great hunger it has for discards. Generally the deck can actually land on all 4 of the main monsters pretty easily - going first your goal in a lot of games is Apollo + Savage + Dragoon + A-Bomb. Going second you're trying to play through negates and break boards with Dragoon + Abomb, and/or OTK with Borrelsword Dragon.  Added a small Artifact package to the deck. I think Lancea is just good as a hand trap right now, particularly against Virtual World, and the deck can make Dagda easily through Needlefibre in its normal combos, or as an alternative to Dark Dragoon if you don't have a card to pitch, with Unchained Abomination helping trigger Dagda and the Scythe, particularly alongside a Rokket Tracer. This gives you something to do when you can make Needlefiber but can't extend underneath Apollousa to make Elpy, and serves as a Buster Lock alternative.

Forget combo return to monke

This is a hybrid strategy of 2 of my favorite archetypes, ABC and Shaddoll. There's a surprisingly high amount of synergy between the two strategies and opening with a couple of playmakers can lead to some absurdly good boards.  The primary plan is to go first and try to establish ABC-Dragon Buster and El Shaddoll Winda on turn 1. This puts the opponent in an extremely bad position to try and play from since Winda restricts the actions they can take each turn while ABC can clean up their much more manageable board. Any opening with Union Hangar and a Doll will allow this opening since you can turn your 2 ABC monsters into a Verte Anaconda and then copy a fusion spell and use Anaconda as the dark monster.  Going 2nd is still a fine place to be in. Shaddoll Fusion obviously shines here and we still have enough room to run the Shaddoll OTK combo along with potentially making Buster along the way.  I don't know if it's necessarily any better than the archetypes by themselves, but it's a lot of fun with the potential to do some really busted stuff!

deck_excerpt: When you realize the last time Rituals were meta was back in Nekroz format
deck_description:
So, as the title suggests, this is a combination of a bunch of stuff, plus a turn skip combo. The combo only requires you to open Deskbot 003, and will be explained below. The Side Deck is still in construction, as I am considering replacing the Invoked engine with the Dogmatika engine.
  1. Normal Summon Deskbot 003
  2. Special Summon Deskbot 001
  3. Link Summon Crystron Halqifibrax
  4. Summon another 001 from your Deck
  5. Link Summon Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon
  6. Summon 3 tokens, reviving both 001s, and summoning 2 Herald of the Arc Light
  7. Overlay into Gallant Granite, activating his effect to search for Gigantes, and Herald's effect for Amorphactor Pain, the Imagination Dracoverlord
  8. Activate Aurora's effect, tributing the third token and Gallant for Mecha Phantom Beast Coltwing, searching for Earth Chant
  9. Activate Coltwing's effect, summoning 2 tokens and both 001s
  10. Synchro Summon a third Herald and an Old Entity Cthugua
  11. Summon the Gigantes from your hand, and then overlay all 4 monsters to make Primathmech Alembertian
  12. Cthugua will let you draw a card, and Alembertian will let you search Thunder of Ruler
  13. Your detached Herald will let you search Black Luster Soldier - Super Soldier
  14. Ritual Summon Amorphactor Pain using Super Soldier
  15. Set Thunder of Ruler and as many face-downs as possible in case your opponent has Spell Speed 2 Spell/Trap Removal, as they can MST your Thunder of Ruler during their Draw Phase
  16. Pass turn, activating Thunder of Ruler to skip their entire turn
  17. Next turn, make Accesscode Talker using Aurora and Alembertian
  18. And with that, you should have a 5300 AT with 2 pops and a 2950 Amorphactor Pain, which should be enough for lethal
What happens if you don't open the combo? Or if it gets interrupted? Or what if you opened Coltwing, the only garnet? That is why the rest of the deck is there. And there you have it, a fun, interacting, and engaging combo that you will certainly not get bored of by the fifth time.

deck_excerpt: A Satellite Cannon Deck with a spacecraft theme. Satellite Cannon takes center stage with support that gets it onto the field quickly, cards to give p
deck_description: Get Satellite Cannon onto the field as quickly as possible. This can be done by special summoning a monster then tribute for Satellite Cannon or use a Falchion Beta's effect to special summon Satellite Cannon from the graveyard to the field. When possible combo Satellite Cannon with Machine Duplication Factory to get your fleet out in one turn. Use Luminous Spark or Machine Conversion Factory to give Satellite Cannon as much permanent ATK as possible.  When Satellite Cannon is on the field, goad your target into attacking when it has little ATK then play Mirror Force, Rising Energy, or special summon Vic Viper T301 to boost the ATK enough and destroy 1 or more monsters on the field. If the Opponent is hesitant, use Battle Mania to force their hand. Limiter Removal should be used sparingly and only if its use can ensure certain victory, or in an emergency if you can summon Satellite Cannon from your Graveyard on your next turn.  The Side Deck offers A-Assault Core if you prefer to use union monsters to bolster Satellite Cannon and offer more protection, as well as Cyber Repair Plant, Seal of Orichalcos, and Threatening Roar as alternatives to recovery, bolster, and defensive tactics.

deck_excerpt: Dogmatika Eldlich for the January 2021 format.
deck_description: Post banlist Eldlich Dogmatika. This version cut some of the weaker cards for more interaction. Eldlich Dogmatika is two-pronged control deck, that seeks to win by using trap cards and slow, recursive value engines to grind out value in the long game, and in my opinion is the best shell for Dogmatika.  The Dogmatika line-up is 10 cards, and none of this has changed. 3 Nadir Servant are starters that search your Dogmatika monsters (Ecclesia) by sending monsters from the extra deck to the graveyard. This is a really powerful effect, since you can send cards like Wind Pegasus, or Nt'ss to get free interaction off of your search. More often, you can send Titaniklad, making this card essentially an Ecclesia that searchs both Fleurdelis and Punishment, which is insane. Ecclessia is your starter that searches interaction - in this deck it is a Normal Summon, and while you do dip into the extra deck most of the space is devoted to sending, and I'd say most games when things are going well you don't make any extra deck plays at all. Fleurdelis is a non-targeting negate and a beat-stick, and the deck's main output for damage. Punishment, however, is straight broken - for the cost of locking yourself out of the extra deck on your next turn, you can send 1 card from the extra deck to the GY to pop 1 monster card on the field (with less ATK than the sent monster). With N'tss this is a 2 for 1, but this is also a recursive engine thanks to Titaniklad, which really helps improve the deck's already stellar grind game. 1 Shaddoll Schism is here, just as a Trap card you can add to your hand by sending Apkallone from the extra deck, and then discard 1. This means Nadir Servant now doubles as both a way to get Golden Lord binned, but also as fodder to resurrect him. This 1 brick is extremely profitable IMO.  For Eldlich, thing have changed. We're still on 3 Golden Lord, but despite Cursed Eldland being such a big card, I decided I needed interactive cards to help get the game slowed down more than the consistency boost and Eldlich combos. We're also down to 2 Hauquero and 0 White Eldlixer. Too many games the White Eldlixer was just a dead card, and while this does technically reduce the power of Eldlich combos, the deck still puts up interaction like a mother, and I'd rather focus on getting things into a grind game to capitalize on my grindy engines.  For interactive cards we're at 15 total. Book of Moon is the best negative 1 in the game, useful both for helping break boards and for stalling people in making them. I don't normally love this card, but I think it is good in Eldlich and I wanted a tech option that was a Spell/Trap. Cosmic Cyclone seems really good in the main right now, what with a lot of the top decks taking advantage of trap cards in some way, and with many of those trap cards having GY effects. Doesn't hurt against Mine either. Imperm + Ash + Nibiru is just a pretty standard hand trap line-up for the format - these are good generic traps that hit most of the format. Imperm seems a little weak against Virtual World, but it has some uses there, and being a trap means there are a lot of benefits to running it in this shell. Good hand traps are good.  Extra deck is exactly the same - a lot of things for us to send with Dogmatika cards, and a handful of "greatest hits" for when we DO have access to the extra deck.

deck_name: Scrap deck, tried to make it as consistent as possible
deck_excerpt: Scrap, 2020-ish , easy to learn, easy to disrupt, fun to play
deck_description: The deck mostly lives with its Dragons so you try to get them out as soon as possible. However Scrap Dragon Turbo has never really been the meta so don't expect to compete on national levels with this deck profile, especially since it literally dies to any form of disruption. The strategy is to get out Scrap Dragon or Twin Dragon and recycle Scrap Chimera back to the hand using anothe Scrap's effect so you can easily replace the Dragon in case he dies. Atomic is only in here for being the "biggest" Scrap Dragon despite arguably being the worst if we are trying to break through a field. However he can easily mess with GY-setups which many decks are centered around nowadays. Scrap Factory and Shark in hand will usually result in a Twin Dragon and a Wyvern as well as whatever you can come up with using the other 3 cards. I won't guarantee the deck will perform greatly but I will guarantee a certain degree of fun while playing it which is the most important in my opinion and Scraps just feel so underappreciated except for Recycler who funnily enough has no real place in a pure-ish Scrap build due to him being the only machine that would be run in the deck. You can build the deck more around him but the consistency of the Scrap engine would suffer from that.

deck_name: Crush Cards Dragon Link deck December 2020
deck_excerpt: THIS DECK WAS USED IN THIS VIDEO https://youtu.be/jhweGd05AeQ  Crush Cards video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1fs1OqZfGeM&t=532s  PLEASE SUBSC
deck_description: THIS DECK WAS USED IN THIS VIDEO https://youtu.be/jhweGd05AeQ  Crush Cards video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1fs1OqZfGeM&t=532s  PLEASE SUBSCRIBE AND THANK YOU.  Add me on discord: Soulburner777#8301 Dm me for duels on edopro or dueling nexus

The idea for the deck is to use the Lightsworn mill engine to help spam your main boss monsters and also be used for link/synchro/XYZ plays. The Main Core of this deck is Raiden, Lumina, Solar Recharge, Charge of Light Brigade, and Chaos Searcher. Everything else can get searched out through milling or by effects of Charge/Chaos Searcher or Omni when summoned.  Ideally to start out your play you want Raiden in your GY (or another Lightsworn), Lumina on hand, 1 random card to discard (Raiden if he isn't in Grave). You take out Raiden, mill 2, and synchro into Michael or F.A. Dawn. But if you can special summon another level 4, either synchro into Chaos Ruler or XYZ Minerva as a starting play. Chaos Space helps a lot getting rid of dead Chaos Monsters or Wulf/Felis on your hand and get another Chaos monster into your hand that can't be a normal summon. I would suggest going for Chaos Valkyra, or Black Dragon/White Dragon depending on what you are discarding. If you banish one light or dark monster that can't be normal summon from your grave while Chaos Space is in Grave, you can banish Chaos Space shuffle that monster back into your deck, and draw 1 card. This way you can recycle certain Lightsworns (Wulf/Felis), JD, or your chaos monsters. Chaos Valkyra is an absolutely amazing card in this deck, it can be special summoned easily, and when she is banished, she works like a Foolish Burial but it will negate its effects for the rest of the turn. However, if you need a certain monster in the grave, she is still good! You don't need to run multiple copies of JD anymore, 1 is good enough. The majority of the time you don't need JD around to win games but having JD is helpful. I won many games without JD and even side JD out. Your extra deck and your other boss monsters can win you games. Take full advantage of Trisula (both versions of the LVL 9 and the upcoming level 11 version) because it will help you clear the field by banishing problem cards and do some hand control on your opponent.
One of the biggest problems with this deck is drawing into Wulf, Felis, or Chaos monsters while you have nothing in your GY or ways to get rid of them. It does happen but it is something Lightsworn players pray it won't happen, ideally, you want something to normal to summon at least like Raiden (especially), Lumina, Lyla, Twilightsworns or anything that can be Normal Summoned as a worst-case scenario.
The main reason why I decided to main Ghost Ogre instead of Effect Veiler or Ash Blossom is that you want to be able to take out problematic cards early on instead of just negating it so your opponent either has to waste resources or couldn't do certain combo plays or they still have the problematic card still around to use in their turn. For example, if someone has out True King of All Calamities, out on the field, you still have to waste resources to get rid of a 3k beatstick if you didn't draw good/screwed up in your combo plays. Also, it is an LVL 3 light tuner that can be used for XYZ or Synchro plays or used for banishing for light materials in the grave/used for discard for Chaos Searcher. Omni Dragon Brotaur is such a helpful card, even though it is LVL 1, you can easily have link monsters that require LVL 1 monster as material in extra, or used for other Synchro/Link plays. It can Special Summon itself from the grave, help you get rid of dead cards from hand, and get out a search for a dragon type or a different type of monster on the field to hand. Chaos Dragon Levianeer and Chaos Emperor are fine running at one. However, I do recommend running multiple Chaos Creators because there is a lot of plays and combos you can do with it. Twilightsworn Lumina, Lyla, and Ryko are the three best Twilightsworns, they are also darks that can be banished for Chaos summons and search targets for Charge of The Light Brigade. I run 1 Lyla and 1 Twilightsworn Lyla because they are okay normal summons if you don't have anything else, pop a backrow for those decks that do run and help with mills. I tun 1 Twilightsworn Ryko because it helps to get rid of problematic cards on-field by banishing. I run 2 Twilightsworn Lumina because you will banish a lot, or your opponent will banish one of your Lightsworns, and she one of your few ways to retrieve them back. For Extra Deck, You only need 1 Minerva, I hardly go into her after starting plays. She an amazing at 1st and 2nd turn (if she survives) and a field nuke when need to crash into problematic monsters on the field (usually most duel goes up to 5 turns before it is game over if no 1st turn OTKs). You can easily recycle her if you need it with Chaos Space or Chaos Creator (she won't have material but if you need to crash and need the mills). If you are going turn 1, I would also suggest going for F.A. Dawn 1st if you can because negativing spells/traps are more important, you should go for Michael to get rid of problematic monsters or cards on the field. Chaos Ruler does 2 things for you, mill and get whatever monster you need to your hand. PSY-Framelord is the best troll in the deck and helps recycle cards when needed. LVL 9 Trishula and LVL 11 one (coming out with the Ice Barrier Structure deck) are some of the best Synchros to go into. LVL 11 Trishula has a floating effect that gets out Trishula LVL 9 (though effects are negated it comes out as a 3300 beatstick), Skill Drains your opponent monsters currently on the field and cuts their atk in half when it destroyed. Number 38 is something you would easily go into a lot, as you aren't main-ing key backrow removers like MST/Twister you want to be able to negative a spell/trap here and there, and also it protects your weaker monsters when needed. Abyss Dweller is a meta call. You can run Leviair because you are going to banish a lot of monsters on both your side and your opponents. But the main reason why I decided to not run it because Chaos Creator a better Leviair and I decided to tech-in I:P Maskerena. Knightmare Phoenix help with getting rid of backrow and Unicorn can help with getting rid of backrow or monsters by shuffling them back into the deck, they are stable Link with little explaining needed. Curious is an okay Link monster to get out, gives you a mill, a foolish but most importantly, you can get any card from your grave to your hand if your opponent destroys it. Saryuja and Bow of the Goddess are necessary Link-4s to have. I:P Maskerena is a good turn on if you need to go into Knightmares or Bow of the Goddess during your opponent's turn as a way to disturb their plays. Side Deck; Your side deck should be against whatever the current meta/or stuff your opponents can side against you or you know they have certain cards that can ruin your plays such as Macro/Skill Drain etc. But at the same time, you want to make your opponent's back row hates be dead as possible a the majority of cards I am running in my side deck are almost all hand traps. Except 2, Called by the Grave and Harpie's Feather Duster. Although I also suggest looking into D.D. Crows, Prohibition, Goddess Skuld's Oracle, Twister/MST, Lost Wind (you can activate from the grave), Breakthrough Skill (you can activate from the grave), and Phantom Knights' Fog Blade.

deck_excerpt: Witchrafter deck focused on shutting down spell usage with secret village and draw power with minor ED support.
deck_description:
This Witchcrafter deck's true power is dependent on getting out Secret village on turn one, and using any of the minor Witches to Special Summon WC Haine. Secret village will either shut your Opp. from using spells that turn (unless Eldlich) or force them to NS a spellcaster to which you can then use Haine's quick effect to pop said Spellcaster thus rendering them unable to use spells UNLESS they can react with a quick play spell. One way to get around this is setting WC Unveiling and immediately using it on your Opp.'s turn to SS any withcrafter from your hand, and with Unveiling's effect being used that turn, your Opp. can no longer react to Haine's pop effect since WC Unveiling states "Special Summon 1 "Witchcrafter" monster from your hand, and if you do, your opponent cannot activate cards or effects in response to the activation of your Spellcaster monster effects for the rest of this turn".  Magicians' souls can help by being relatively easy to SS along with having draw power, or you can side in Jester Confit if you aren't comfortable sending a lvl 6 or higher Spellcaster to GY while also sacrificing ability to draw, but Souls is preferred since it can help send the WC traps to GY for their banish effects. In the event you are without a Spellcaster on field, WC Genni can help alleviate your spell restriction by banishing her along with a WC Spell that can help you get a Witchcrafter out. Don't like banishing? Well don't worry cause WC Patronus will help you bring back ANY Spellcaster Banished or in GY to your Deck or Extra Deck while also bringing a WC spell to your hand, which can definitely help against flood gates like Dimensional Fissure, but be warned because Extra Deck Spellcasters that were bainshed by Pot of Extravagance cannot be retrieved due to them being face-down. Extra deck:
  • Magistus Artemis is only in here to easily send a  minor Witchcrafter to GY if you don't need to use their Field eff, but their GY eff is needed.
  • Relinquished Anima can help clear your Opp.s' field but is reliant on having a Monster infront of the Extra Mon. space.
  • Akashic can help bounce cards and can co-link with Magistus Artemis or Anima to mill one card from your deck.
  • Day-break is mostly here just because he's a spellcaster, but he can help clear field as well if you can SS a Spellcaster to his zones.
  • Selene is a little hard to get since this deck, and Witchcrafters in general, struggle with Monster Flooding. She was added because shes a spellcaster and can help retrieve them from GY, but again she's a little hard to bring out and she's only useful if there are spells on the field and GY which might be rare due to Secret Village and maybe Genni's banish effect
  • RE dragoon can be sided but I avoid it due to you adding 2-3 possible dead cards in your hand/deck.
Ideal turn 1 field (IMO):
  • SecretVillage
  • WC Haine for pops
  • WC Bystreet to protect Haine (WC Schmietta can send this to GY with her banish eff if she was Trib. to SS Haine)
  • WC Patronus (To retrieve the WC used to SS Haine and bring discard ammo) or WC Unveiling (Dependent on having a WC in your hand but allows for "Spell Speed 4" Haine)
  • (Optional) WC Verre for negs (Only possible really if she's in hand along with Unveiling)
Sorry if this was messy to read, I made it round 2am lmao, and if you have any additional questions on this deck or Witchcrafter effect combos or critiques, feel free to reach out :). Hope you enjoy the deck, and have fun using it. Konami more Witchcrafter support please

deck
This is A pure Harpie Deck

Read and you will be more successful with this deck.  Approximately 100$ us for every card.  MAIN MONSTER   For our first monster, we have Magical Musketeer Starfire one of the best magical musketeer monsters that lets you play a Magical Musket card from your hand like all the ones in this deck and an sp from the deck if you play it in her column. Next, we have what I think is the best main deck Magical Musketeer monster Magical Musketeer Caspar lets you play a magical musket card from your hand (going to stop saying this because they all say this) and his column effect is You can add 1 "Magical Musket" card from your Deck to your hand, but not a card with the same name as that activated card great for keeping cards in your hand. Next, we got draw power Magical Musketeer Kidbrave column effect to discard a Magical Musket card draw 2 cards nice plus one. Second last on the list we have Magical Musketeer Doc column effect brings a magical musket card from your gy to your hand but not the one you played this is good for bringing back your best card like Magical Musket - Cross-Domination. Last and least Magical Musketeer Calamity column effect sp a Magical Musket card from your gy .      For the Kaiju engine, we have 3 Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju which can destroy your opponent's powerful monsters and has the smallest atk of the Kaijus at 2200. The last Kaijus we have is Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju with a powerful atk of 3300 which you would like to summon on your side of the field to finish the game.  The last main monster we have is Effect Veiler which is a great stun card.   MAIN SPELLS  First for the spells we have Interrupted Kaiju Slumber a great card to destroy all your opponent's monsters and get Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju, to your field.  Now for the best Magical Musket card Magical Musket - Cross-Domination it negates effect at turns atk to 0. Last for spells we have Pot of Desires just a simple draw card.    Main traps.  First up for traps we have Magical Musket - Desperado a simple and good magical musket card. It just a destroyed face-up card on the field but your opponent will not see it coming if you play it from your hand. Number two for the traps we got 

Magical Musket - Crooked Crown it sp a Magical Musketeer card from your hand and takes away a monster zone from your opponent for the turn. Second, to last for the traps we have Magical Musket - Last Stand which is a spell trap negate. For the last card in the main deck, we have Magical Musket - Dancing Needle which can banish 3 cards from any player's gy which is great because almost everyone is using gy effects. 

  EXTRA DECK   Ok, let’s start off with the boss card Magical Musketeer Max he is the key to this deck he generates your resources so you can keep negating your opponent and win the long game. Next in line, it’s Salamangreat Almiraj and Secure Gardna just in case anything happens and you need to protect yourself. For a win condition, we have Borrelsword Dragon he can finish off games with powerful atks and his powerful effect. For another powerful link for I put in Unchained Abomination a strong link 4 that can destroy your opponent's field. For XYZ we have Number 39: Utopia, 

Number C39: Utopia Ray, Number S39: Utopia the Lightning go into utopia then ray last go into lightning for two 5000 atk swings. You could also use Number 39: Utopia Double with Double or Nothing!. The last cand in the extra deck is Number 75: Bamboozling Gossip Shadow, a good negate card for your extra lv 3 monsters. (going into your extra deck aside from Magical Musketeer Max is not always the best idea.) 

  SIDE DECK  Starting now with your side deck we have Artifact Lancea, a powerful card with lots of the meta banishing as cost Eldlich dino Virtual World. Next up Gnomaterial, this card is very useful against link climb decks. For anti draw power, we have Droll & Lock Bird feel tired of your opponent searching and drawing out so many cards now they can only do one with this powerful card. For the second last monster, we have an extra Effect Veiler. For a powerful going second card, it’s Dinowrestler Pankratops, a free sp, and pop. For spell trap removal  I put in Cosmic Cyclone. For the only trap and last card, it’s Red Reboot a powerful crap negate card making it so your opponent can not activate traps for the rest of the turn.    Deck strategy.   The strategy of this deck is to build up your board slowly while you stop your opponent from making theirs with spells and traps. This deck likes going second because you can break your opponent's board with kujus and use Magical Musketeer Max to get you more spells/traps. Hopeful then your opponent has used lots of their resources already and 2-3 stuns will leave them helpless. This deck can force a slow game really easily with the kujus but if that doesn't work you have a side deck full of choices that can slow your opponent down and get you the win.     Decks to watch out for. (top control decks.) deck_excerpt: A OTK CyDra deck ready to go for January 2021.
deck_description: Returned to YGO after taking a break due to the Eldich-Adamancipator duumvirate and rebuilt my CyDra deck. It's pretty similar to my previous deck posted here, primarily made for going second, however cards in the side deck maximise winning potential. The strategy is plain and simple, going second: break the opponent's board and swing for the KO. Going first: stun and set up a board wipe or lock the opponent out of summoning, before going in for the KO in turn 3. Monsters: Cyber Dragons: Cyber Dragon - Run at three for the benefit of Machine Duplication, which remains the deck's win condition. Seeing this in the opening hand when going second isn't an issue given it's effect, however it can brick if going first and you have no other cards to assist in bringing it out. Cyber Dragon Core - The deck's main starter and MVP, ran at three. When summoned, this will, if uninterrupted by your opponent, will add 1 "Cyber" spell/trap to your hand. This card's secondary effect (activated in the GY) can also help reconstruct your board if your opponent has cleared your side of the field monsters, by bringing a Cyber Dragon monster from your deck to your hand at the cost of banishing Core from the Graveyard. Target #1 for Machine Duplication. Cyber Dragon Herz - Again, ran at three as this is a Machine Duplication target. Both effects are useful, although you are far more likely to get mileage out of Herz mid-game when special summoned for Rank 5 XYZ plays. This card also synergises well with Galaxy Soldier, given Galaxy Soldier's special summoning condition of discarding a light monster, this card brings a "Cyber Dragon" to the hand to facilitate the special summon of the second Galaxy solider - instant XYZ summon into Cyber Dragon Nova. Cyber Dragon Nachster - Ran at two, as this is the only Machine Duplication target that can brick on turn 1; without another monster (preferably a Cyber Dragon) or Machine Duplication in hand, this is as good as useless. This card really shines when your GY is filled with Machine monsters with the magical 2100 ATK or DEF value, however be wary that once activated you can no longer special summon non-Machine monsters for the remainder of the turn. Cyber Eltanin - Board wipe, "sends" rather than destroys monsters and does not target, which is incredibly useful for dealing with Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. Searchable, used as an alternative and counter to the Red-Eyes package. Other monsters: Galaxy Soldier - A Cyber Dragon in all but name. This is the go-to card to make Cyber Dragon Infinity as it leaves your ordinary Cyber Dragons available for other uses. Synergises with Cyber Dragon Herz very well and is searchable through Cyber Repair Plant. In addition, if you have already summoned Chimeratech Rampage Dragon and these remain floating in your deck (a brick waiting to be drawn), these are ideal cards to discard to grant Rampage the additional attacks. Ran at two, as three increases the likelihood that multiples could be drawn and bricking on turn 1. Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju - Ideal for removing a troublesome opposing monster and is easily removable thanks to Chimeratech Fortress Dragon (a good rule would be to run one Fortress for every Jizukiru in the Main deck). Searchable through Cyber Repair Plant. Ran at one, however this is a very good candidate to increase to two. Dinowrestler Pankratops - Fantastic card to provide an easy bit of spot removal. Handtraps: Currently, I'm only running Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, increased from two to three, as it's by far the most effective handtrap in the game. I also considered the PSY-Framegear Gamma package, however I've found that with the other spells/traps/handtraps included in the deck, it's a bit overkill and can make the deck even more bricky. Spells: Cyber Emergency - The ROTA of the deck, with built in protection at the cost of a discard. Ran at three. Cyber Repair Plant - An extender that relies on you having at least one "Cyber Dragon" in the GY. Searches the majority of the monsters in the Main Deck, however is a hard once per turn and given the prerequisite, I wouldn't advise increasing to three copies. Cyber Revsystem - Another useful extender; Monster Reborn for "Cyber Dragon" with the bonus option of allowing you to special summon a Cyber Dragon from the hand. Not particularly useful for your Extra Deck Monsters (barring Cyber Dragon Sieger), however you have Nachster to bring them back from the GY. Could increase to two, however I prefer having a copy of Monster Reborn. Machine Duplication - Your win condition. Target one "Cyber Dragon" with less than 500 ATK, special summons two Cyber Dragons from the deck. If this resolves, it's usually game over. Having this at three does make the deck very bricky, however given the risk/reward involved, the benefit outweighs the cost. Overload Fusion - Facilitates your OTK. Ran at one because having multiples in hand at the cost of an extender is not fun and Verte Anaconda provides an easily available search. The only target is Chimeratech Rampage Dragon, however it's the only one you really need. Cyberload Fusion - Quick play fusion card that also can facilitate an OTK, for the purpose of bringing out Cyber Twin Dragon or Rampage. In terms of using it, this is best activated during the battle phase, after all other monsters have attacked, bring out Cyber Twin Dragon for 5600 points of damage (better still when this is combined with Sieger). Lightning Storm - Going second staple, Harpie's Feather Duster + Raigeki. Budget alternatives: Dark Hole, Cosmic Cyclone, Twin Twisters Dark Ruler No More - Going second, helps break boards by nullifying monster effects. Foolish Burial - Staple for seeding the GY and activating Repair Plant. Monster Reborn - Useful as an extender and to bring back boss monsters in a pinch. Traps: Cybernetic Overflow - Great card. Maximum 3 cards popped on your opponent's side of the field and if destroyed by card-effect, you can search another "Cyber" Spell/Trap from your deck. I've added the second copy which is usually sided out into the main. Banishes Cyber Dragons to set up for Cyberload Fusion. Red Reboot - Wins you games! Extra Deck: Chimeratech Fortress Dragon - Useful to dispose of your Kaiju, and wiping the field clean in mirror matches or anything that uses a Machine type. Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon - Snatches opponent's monsters out of the Extra Monster Zone, what's not to love? Chimeratech Rampage Dragon - Insanely powerful card. Has the potential to act as a Harpie's Feather Duster (depending on the number of monsters used for its Fusion Summon) and can attack three times. Ran at two as space is an issue in the Extra Deck. Cyber Twin Dragon - More potent than Cyber End Dragon, hands down. This card is a game winner if brought out with Cyberload Fusion during the battle phase. Cyber Eternity Dragon - Generic Cyberload Fusion Target, 4000 DEF, if there's a Fusion monster in the GY it can't be targeted or be destroyed by card effect. Cyber Dragon Nova - Ran at two, for safety, as everyone hates it when the smashy rock comes down! Cyber Dragon Infinity - Best card to bring out when forced to go first (paired with Cybernetic Overflow). Can suck up an opposing monster and provides a negate. Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder - One of the best XYZ themed cards in the Meta, synergises well with Infinity and Nova. Cyber Dragon Sieger - Built in Limiter Removal, best used in conjunction with Chimeratech Rampage Dragon Predaplant Verte Anaconda - Searches Overload Fusion and Cyberload Fusion! Salamangreat Almiraj - Turns on Cyber Repair Plant and provides protection for Extra Deck Monsters Linkuriboh - Similarly to Almiraj, turns on Repair Plant, but is exclusively for Herz and Nachster Relinquished Anima - Makes an opponent pay for zone deployment mistakes and easily accessible via Herz and Nachster. Side Deck: Heat Wave - Cyber Dragon hates going first, however this card shuts down most decks by stopping Effect Monsters from being summoned until your next draw phase, giving you an opportunity to OTK on turn 3 Evenly Matched - A particularly nasty way of clearing the opponent's board. It might stop you from OTKing on Turn 2, but it's definitely worth running at three! Moved from the Main Deck to the side as I'm using Lightning Storm in the Main Deck. Appointer of the Red Lotus - Self explanatory, removing an opponent's starters, extenders or combo pieces from their hand can ruin their day! Solemn Strike - Generic stun, a potential alternative is Solemn Warning. Sided in going first. Torrential Tribute - A gut punch of a card that I'm so glad is making a bit of a comeback. Sided in going first. Other cards to consider: Cyber Dragon Vier - Suprisingly useful link-fodder and a helpful chain-blocker for Cyber Dragon Core. I've heard of people running this at more than one for these reasons, however if this was the sole monster in my hand on Turn 1, I'd be very disappointed. Given that this is also not a Machine Duplication target, I would not advise having more than two in the deck. Removed from the Main Deck as whilst it's nice to have, using the slot over other cards wasn't justifiable. Chaos Dragon Levianeer - Easily accessible beatstick in the mid-late game, 3000 ATK is not to be sniffed at. The banishing summoning condition synergises with the deck very well and comes with a built in Monster Reborn-effect for additional link-fodder. As it is 8 stars, this also can be used as material for the XYZ summon of Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star (if played). This card can brick and therefore is ran at one. If you are not running Dingirsu, I would suggest replacing this with another copy of Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju. I've removed this from the Main Deck as whilst Dingirsu is great, I wasn't seeing it often enough to justify a spot. Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star - Provides a negate where your cards would be destroyed and can pop an opponent's card upon its Special Summon. As above. Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess - Potential 3200 ATK and provides four negates, a budget alternative would be Borrelsword Dragon. Removed for Extra Deck Space. Different Dimension Ground - For mirror matches and to really mess with decks that rely on the GY. Whilst useful, this wasn't seeing enough play and was cut. Infinite Impermanence - Would have been included, however it's not been having the best showing recently, but it could make a return in the future.

deck_excerpt: Galaxy/Photon deck December 2020 (Advice wanted!)  (Also, am I the only one who gets gundam vibes from AA-ZEUS's artwork?)
deck_description: ...Alright so...here is my first Galaxy/Photon deck, revolving around Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Ex Dragon. I'm very much new to that archetype, in terms of playing it. Up until now, I've only played against it. Because of that, some advice on how to improve this deck would be GREATLY appreciated.     Anyways, this deck's main goal is to go second because of Cipher Ex Dragon's first effect, which lets you detach two Xyz Materials from it to make your LIGHT monsters untargetable until the end of your opponent's turn. Basically, your strategy is to summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon (without using its effect), then summon Cipher Ex Dragon with it and use that effect. Then you attack with your Xyz monsters, and use Cipher Ex Dragon to summon AA-ZEUS during your Main Phase 2. And because AA-ZEUS is a LIGHT monster, your opponent can't target it with any card effects until their turn is over.     The end result of this strategy is that your opponent will be left to deal with an untargetable, 3000 ATK beatstick that can nuke the field. And if Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon is detached to activate AA-ZEUS's effect, Afterglow Dragon can either use its second effect to attach a Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from the hand or Deck to ZEUS so that it can activate its effect again. Alternatively, Afterglow Dragon's effect can summon it to your field so that you can deal at least 6000 battle damage on your next turn.     So, the Ace Monsters of this deck are Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon, Photon Dragon, Cipher Ex Dragon, and AA-ZEUS.  Because of this deck's primary goal, and AA-ZEUS's appearance, this deck is named "Galaxy Gundam."

deck_excerpt: 100% NIBIRU PROOF Virtual World deck and Combo!
deck_description:
Hello and welcome to my Virtual World Build! This new deck that I made does not require the new trap gate to be nibiru proof, this new card is like the icing on the cake. It is very easy to achieve and here’s what you need to do it and what you get when you do it -    What you need -   Lulu/Lili + Kawaloon + any 1 VW monster except Nyannyan   What you end on -     
  • The entire thing is Nibiru proof (Gossip shadow)
  • VFD (Free win - no monster effects on the field for opponent)
  • Number 75: Gossip Shadow (negate if you haven’t used it already on nibiru)
  • Geomathmech Final Sigma (great against control decks, OTK card for next turn, unaffected by other cards, is a 3k beat stick that does double damage while on the extra monster zone)
  • Virtual world gate: Chuche (shuffle 2 VW cards from banish zone into deck to pop 1 during opponent’s turn)
    Virtual world is a Tier 1 competition of the current metagame and took - 1st LCS 8, 2nd LCS 8 and 1st LCS 9. The deck is very powerful being able to being able to turbo out True King of all Calamities very consistently, end on zeus with 4 materials at the worst case, be nibiru proof (number 75), Have multiple sources of removal (Utopia Beyond to counter Dragoon, Jaja, Break Sword, Constellar M7) and have a level 9 synchro monster on the field that if sent to the graveyard off of true king or simply just sent there - can recur itself back and is literally a Macros Cosmos (any card sent from the field to the graveyard is banished instead). This is all as of now and it gets better. There is new support of this deck that makes the deck more consistent and even better! The combos also end on a much higher note! The 2 new cards coming are Virtual world Rabbit - Tutu and Virtual World Gate - Zhuangwoo. Tutu is trash so this deck does not run it but Zhuangwoo is actually really good. You never really want to set it because it’s field effect is really bad. It is only good because of it’s monster reborn effect you can activate by banishing it from the graveyard. If you draw it you can simply discard it to resolve Qinglong so it is not a brick. It can extend the combo and also serve as an extender paired up with Foolish Burial goods!    If you want to learn how to do this combo, I highly recommend watching my Youtube video - in it I explain the entire deck in-depth and all of my card choices and also tell you how to do the combo. In this video I only do the Nibiru proof combo so if you want to learn how to do the ‘normal’ combos as well check out my other video! I also have a 1st Place LCS 8 Virtual world deck video if you are interested in that. Also consider answering the poll question down below! Today’s poll question is: What are your favorite decks of all time, and what is your favorite archetype/card?   Link to the video (Nibiru proof combo) - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wWhnwYCk0Uo&t=1s   Link to the video with the ‘normal’ combos- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wO1BEmTULP4&t=7s   Link to the 1st Place LCS 8 video -https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EAPKAoKrm30   Thanks and I will see you next time! :D

deck_excerpt: A deck utilizing the "Gladiator Beast" archetype, an aggressive beatdown deck with various strategies revolving around battle and Special Summoning wh
deck_description:
This is my take at a "Gladiator Beast" deck. Originally, "Gladiator Beasts" were a battle-focussed archetype with a unique gimmick which is referred to as "taging out", in which a "Gladiator Beast" monster could shuffle itself into the deck after being part of a battle and summon another "Gladiator Beast" from the deck which would then activate some sort of effect. They still have this ability and work with it, but the more modern support also gave them ways to tag without even attempting a battle while providing the deck with various other cards and strategies to make use off.

First and foremost, the Normal Monster in the archetype in form of "Gladiator Beast Andal" is absolutely crucial. Unlike various other archetypes that have Normal Monsters in their ranks, "Gladiator Beast Andal" is a solid beater, can be used for various other summons in the deck and is a consistent Special Summon to use via "Rescue Rabbit" and "Unexpected Dai".

The Effect "Gladiator Beast" Monsters I run are one copy of "Gladiator Beast Attorix", both for the graveyard setup as well as her ability to change her level in order to be used for certain Fusion monsters, two copies of "Gladiator Beast Bestiari" for his backrow removal effect and because he is of paramount importance to summon "Gladiator Beast Gyzarus" from the Extra Deck, one copy of "Gladiator Beast Equeste" for the very useful ability of recycling "Gladiator Beast" Spells, one copy of "Gladiator Beast Darius" for an in-archetypal "Monster Reborn", one copy of "Gladiator Beast Noxious" for yet more graveyard setup, the effect of preventing one attack with the added bonus of being able to tag during the opposing turn, one copy of "Gladiator Beast Vespasius" as more high-level Fusion material that can Special Summon itself and two copies of "Gladiator Beast Augustus" for yet more high-level monster for the Extra Deck summons with the added bonus of being able to swarming the field with "Gladiator Beasts" and also triggering their effects since they still get summoned correctly. The generic monster options aside from "Rescue Rabbit" are three copies of "Test Tiger", which are more swarming and allow more hands you draw to go into "Test Panther" and three copies of "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" for interruption that you can and should absolutely afford to play.

The backrow has three "Unexpected Dai" for "Gladiator Beast Andal", three "Gladiator Beast's Comeback" for various reasons but mostly as a play extender, three copies of "Gladiator Proving Ground" as the "Reinforcement of the Army" for "Gladiator Beasts", one "Mind Control" to clear monsters off the opposing field while also gaining material for "Test Panther", "Pot of Avarice" to make "Gladiator Beast" monster available again which allows you to activate cards like "Rescue Rabbit" and "Unexpected Dai" again, one "Gladiator Beast United" to surprise opponents during the Battle Phase by summoning monsters such as "Gladiator Beast Domitianus", three copies of "Gladiator Rejection" as a useful summoning tool and a way to give your monsters targeting protection, one "Gladiator Beast Charge" as a board clear, one copy of "Gladiator Beast War Chariot" as a searchable anti-monster effect Counter Trap and lastly one "Double or Nothing!" for the well-known "Utopia Double" engine.

In terms of the Extra Deck "Gladiator Beasts" actually use quite a lot of the options they have at their disposal. "Gladiator Beast Essedarii" is only in the Extra Deck to have access to another Level 5 "Gladiator Beast" monster if I have enough option in the Level 4 segment but cannot go any higher with the available cards. The aforementioned high-level "Gladiator Beasts" are absolutely necessary as you pretty much always want to summon "Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor", who pretty much summons Extra Deck monsters for free and therefore really pays for himself. Options to summon via "Gladiator Beast Tamer Editor" include "Gladiator Beast Heraklinos" for as many Spell/Trap negates as you want as long as you can pay for it by discarding cards from your hand, or "Gladiator Beast Domitianus" who comes with 3500 ATK, can negate a monster effect per turn and lets you choose what the opponent has to attack. Equally as important in the Extra Deck is the aforementioned "Gladiator Beast Gyzarus", who gets rid of two opposing cards when summoned. Constantly resummoning "Gladiator Beast Gyzarus" is something that is relatively easy in this deck and can clear the field while you are still setting up for an OTK scenario. The main play enabler is "Test Panther", who is summonable with two monsters of which thankfully only one needs to be a "Gladiator Beast" monster, and it fetches "Gladiator Beast" cards on summon while also allowing to "tag out" without the need of an attack. The rest is pretty straightforward: I run the two cards necessary for the "Utopia Double" engine, one "Borrelsword Dragon" since it supports the beatdown strategy really well, "Knightmare Phoenix" against opposing backrow, one copy of "Gladiator Beast Dragases" for the rare scenarios in which he is a better choice than "Test Panther" and one "Link Spider" to make the best out of two copies of "Gladiator Beast Andal" in your starting hand.

I only started writing about "Gladiator Beasts" after a friend of mine asked me to help him build a deck with them, but after I was finished going through them all I had to admit that they are an interesting bunch of cards to work with. I feel like they run out of resources rather quickly but they do perform quite well with some explosive plays while also staying true to their archetype's identity. If you want some more information on "Gladiator Beast", for example about the cards I left out in this 50+ card archetype, then feel free to take a look at my archetype analysis on my blog: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2020/12/19/archetype-analysis-gladiator-beast/.
Eldlich, Dogmatika, Dragoon, Shaddoll
