deck_excerpt: Summon the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon ASAP then win.
deck_description:
Deck made to be played with the original Yu-Gi-Oh! rules, before Synchro summon was created. Summon the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon ASAP then win. Based on a Red-Eyes deck, with lots of high level dragons that you summon from your graveyard. Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon can be quickly summoned thanks to Red-Eyes Fusion, or Curse of Dragonfire  as a backup in case you no longer have access to your Red-Eyes Fusion cards, or even Dragon's Mirror as a last resort. Red-Eyes Fusion can be easily retrieved by using the following cards:
  • Keeper of Dragonic Magic
  • Black Metal Dragon (by kamizaking it, tributing it, etc.)
  • Masked Dragon (by summoning Black Metal Dragon)
  • Red-Eyes Baby Dragon (by searching Black Metal Dragon)
  • Red-Eyes Insight (by searching Red-Eyes Fusion)
Once the Dark Magician is in the GY, summoning a second Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon will be harder (your only options being Keeper of Dragonic Magic, Monster Reborn, Amulet Dragon, and Dragon's Mirror). Dark Magician the Dragon Knight is worth summoning as a replacement (its name is considered "Dark Magician"), as it is a level 8 Dragon monster that will be easier for you to get out of the GY. You should keep  Dragon's Mirror to fusion summon this monster. Those cards allow you to search your deck (and send the found card to either the hand or the graveyard):
  • Keeper of Dragonic Magic
  • Masked Dragon
  • Red-Eyes Baby Dragon
  • Black Metal Dragon
  • The Black Stone of Legend
  • Dragon Ravine
  • Red-Eyes Insight
Those cards allow you to discard cards to the graveyard, either from your hand or directly from your deck:
  • Dragon Ravine (very effective)
  • Red-Eyes Insight
  • The Claw of Hermos
  • Raigeki Break
  • Mirror Force Launcher
  • Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon
Those cards allow you to summon themselves or other monsters from the GY:
  • Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon (easy special summon from hand, special summon other dragons from the GY)
  • Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon (easy tribute and special summon others from the GY)
  • Dragunity Arma Gram (summons himself from the hand or GY)
  • Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair (summons himself from the hand or GY, lots of Dark monsters in the deck)
  • Red-Eyes Wyvern
  • Keeper of Dragonic Magic
  • Decoy Dragon
  • The Black Stone of Legend (summons from the GY indirectly, after 1 turn)
  • Red-Eyes Spirit
  • Return of the Dragon Lords
  • Monster Reborn
As the deck has a lots of high level dragons, those cards help you summon those monsters from your hand:
  • Keeper of the Shrine (very effective)
  • Black Dragon's Chick / Red-Eyes B. Chick
  • Red-Eyes Retro Dragon
  • Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon, Dragunity Arma Gram, Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair by their own effect.
https://youtu.be/VC8JjZLD_Xg

deck_excerpt: Plunder Patroll - post LIVO (artifacts are only in the side deck)
deck_description: Plunder Patroll is a midrange deck which can be really explosive, but it can also play the grind game to an extend. You shouldn´t expect to outgrind something like Eldlich, but most of the time you can.  The new Ravenwing/ Blackfeather (what ever his name is to you) is amazing, it is basically a +2. For the most time you won´t have a problem to mill a Plunder, so u get a free recursion plus a special summon, also if u milled Bluebeard you can special summon him too.  Also if u use Ravenwing + Redbeard to link off into Blackbeard u can equip the redbeard of its own effect and then special summon him back of the effect of Ravenwing, so u got a material for Blackbeard.  Don´t get me started on the possibilities u get with Ravenwing + Goldenhair, for example you can pitch Goldenhair for any effect, then activate Ravenwing to recur her, then use Goldenhairs effect to special her, then u can link em off into Blackbeard. Now you can special Goldenhair from GY again of her effect (since her special summons are two different effects and both can be used once per turn) and if u got an equipped Plunder u could special this one too because of Ravenwing.  As I mentioned this card is amazing, recursion + special summon + replacement for zero cost (since most of the time you will be locked into Plunders anyway).  Now I would like to explain my deck choices. You will be playing 3 of any Plunder monster, because all are at least useable (redbeard) and most of them are really good (Whitebeard/Goldenhair/Ravenwing). 3 Pot of desires, so you play almost anything as 3 and you need the draw power. 3 Shipyarrds, the field spell is amazing it mills and it searches - amazing, therefore also 1 Terraforming. 2 Shipshape ship shipping, honestly you can play 3 of them since this card is very good for discarding and it frees you from a light monster to summon lys and it equips plunder cards, but it´s my least favorable card and I don´t wanna play more than 40 cards. At last 3 booty, amazing card recursion + attribute choice - really important card btw. My handtraps are 3 ash, 2 veiler, 3 imperm and for backrow 2 twin twister.  My extra is nothing special, two of every Plunder (if u aren´t that good or unexperienced with plunder I recommend to ditch the bijinki and play 3 Blackbeards), 1 Dragite for spell/traps, 1 bahamut +toadally for negates+recursion of toadally, 1 white aura whale good almost board wipe which can be chain blocked by the materials for it (not that good in the current format, u could swap it for masquerina), 1 almiraj for goldenhair shenanigans, 1 bujinki for the 1 abyss dweller.  My side deck shows a wide spread of possible cards which can be used, but I really recommend the Kaijus (good outs for Dragun and attributes for u to use).  If u have better choices or feedback let me know :D

deck_excerpt: Mainly just a deck I made to test the flexibility of Phantom Knights
deck_description:
A (Somewhat) Brief History of Phantom Knights

The Phantom Knights (commonly abbreviated as PK) archetype is a Dark-Warrior, rank 3 and 4 toolbox based archetype, that likes to banish it's monsters from the graveyard to activate their effects. originally introduced in 2016 in the set Wing Raiders. From the time the archetype was originally released up to 2019, the deck was, quite lacking to say the least. The archetype in more pure builds had not much going for it, and required a bunch of generic extenders to get plays going. Then 2019 came along, releasing the Legendary Hero Decks. So far the most recent installment in the Legendary Decks series of products, came with a blessing for the PK players (or at least the people who like PK), but a curse to practically everyone else, The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche. This card was and still is an absolutely insane card that boosted the PK deck immensely to the point that in pure builds the best way to play it was Bardiche turbo. Being able to cover a majority of the PK's major weaknesses as an archetype were fixed, being able to both send a PK monster to the graveyard, and set a PK S/T afterwards. This is where the card gets more insane when you remember the PK's best S/T is a trap card that negates, and being able to send The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots to fetch another one from the deck. If Bardiche doesn't get negated, you have one free negate on the board just by summoning the damn thing. The craziest thing about The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche is that the card only requires Dark monsters for its summon, being able to be abused by predominantly Dark decks. This is where the best deck at the time, Orcust, comes in. Orcust was a powerful beast of a deck in 2019 with major consistency and Dingirsu, being able to stack the PK's newfound power on top of it, along with another insanely powerful card at the time, Outer Entity Azathot (basically the VFD of 2019, when being summoned by Phantom Knights' Rank-Up-Magic Launch, also settable through Bardiche btw), It became too much of a trouble where Konami pulled a Firewall Dragon FTK format and didn't hit the actual enablers of these plays until January 2020, Banning Orcust Harp Horror, the main consistency booster of Orcust, Bardiche, for being an insane splashable tool, and Azathot, to let people play the game again. (Oh and the rest of the 2019 meta, everything got banned), Fast forward to September 2020, Konami decided to bring back The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche, to help hype up the upcoming set in November 2020, Phantom Rage, which came with some new Phantom Knights support, which has not only made the purer builds of PK more menacing, but also boosted the power enough to make the deck a rouge competitor in the meta today!

Deck List:

The Phantom Knights

3 The Phantom Knights of Torn Scales: This is the best piece of support the Phantom Knights archetype got in Phantom Rage and for good reason, It's both a starter card, and an extender card. This is a card that you want to play 3 of as much as you can in any PK deck, its insane versatility and reliability as a card in the deck makes it a permanent 3 of in every form of PK. 3 The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak: 3 The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots: 2 The Phantom Knights of Ragged Gloves: 1 The Phantom Knights of Stained Greaves:

The Other Monsters

3 Marauding Captain: This is the second of your 3 normal summons in the deck, being able to turbo out another monster on summon making easy cherubini plays is really, really nice to have. Not every build must play this, but it's one that's used in a lot of builds for it's generi use. A classic card,.remembering the days of GOAT format when this thing was at 2 to make the battle lock less consistent, now that effect of Marauding Captain doesn't come up often nowadays, it's still something to take note of. 3 Tour Guide from The Underworld: The 3rd main normal summon of the deck, has the same first effect as marauding captain but it's type specific but allows you to not need the target you want in hand, it's a duality that is nice to remember, Marauding summons in from hand with only lv restriction, Tour Guide summons from hand or deck with both a type and lv restriction. 2 Graff, Malebranche of The Burning Abyss: This is the main target you want to summon off of Tour Guide, not drawing into Tour Guide is still not much of an issue if you can still make Cherubini to send this card to get it's effect off. Playing 2 of it is ideal because if you draw into it as a 1 of, your combos will require more resources, and playing it at 3 is not ideal in this build since you don't necessarily want to draw into it outside of PK Fire. 2 Cir, Malebranche of The Burning Abyss: This is the target you want to summon off of Graff. Also playing 2 for the same reasons and it's also a harder garnet than Graff if you play it at 1. 1 Farfa, Malebranche of The Burning Abyss: The card you want to summon off of Graff if you go second instead of Cir to help clear up your opponent's board of a troublesome card during your combo. Don't need to run 2 as you aren't always going second, and that it's not entirely dead in hand. ,3 Kagemucha Knight: The best extender in the deck, if you draw this with any other monster, you practically just have a free Cherubini to start off your combos. (It can also chain block your Tour Guide against ash which is really helpful but not insane as imperm is still a card, but even then you still have the materials to go into Cherubini so it wouldn't matter too much.) 1 Psychic Traker & Psychic Wheeleder: You can definitely play more of these if you want but I prefer the Danger!? package because of it's draw power. 1 Danger!? Jackelope? & Danger!? Tsuchinoko?: This little Danger!? package is really nice to play in the deck as they are dark lv 3 monsters that special summon themselves while also setting up the graveyard, albeit randomly, that also draw a card on their summon, play 3 of these if they ever go back to 3. 1 Dark Magician & Red-Eyes Black Dragon: Garnets in every sense of the word, only played in here for the Dragoon engine, an engine that is really helpful in PK as PK can't play through negation as easily as decks like VW or Infernobles. 1 Psy-Frame Driver: Gamma fodder and that's it.

Spells

1 Reinforcement of The Army: One of the most famous cards in the game and for good reason, generic searching fro any warrior monster you need is really helpful. 1 Foolish Burial: 1 Emergency Teleport: 1 Phantom Knights' Rank-Up-Magic Force: 1 Red-Eyes Fusion:

Traps

3 Phantom Knights' Fog Blade:

, Hand Traps

3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring: 3 Infinite Impermanence: 3 Psy-Framegear Gamma: (Im going to finish writing this i swear =-=)
Plunder Patrol (LIOV)

deck_excerpt: A deck featuring the "Digital Bug" archetype, which uses position changing for swarming and field control.
deck_description:
This is my take at building a "Digital Bug" deck. "Digital Bugs" are often labeled as the test version for the "Zoodiac" archetype, since they use their archetypal monsters to stack into other monsters at their disposal. They are, however, a lot weaker due to overall weaker effects, the need for Xyz materials to start Xyz climbing and the focus on position changing. Nonetheless, they gained a support card in Blazing Vortex that helps immensely and makes them a fun little deck that can actually use its gimmick to full effect.

Due to their restrictiveness in summoning by asking for specific Attribute/Type combinations, you will have to run quite a lot of the archetype's monsters. I run three "Digital Bug Resistrider", which is an amazing support card that can manipulate levels, Special Summon itself when a Level 3 Insect monster is Normal Summoned and allows for position changing which benefits the overall strategy. "Digital Bug Centibit" summons monsters from the deck and allows the Xyz monster this monster is material of to attack all opposing defense position monsters. "Digital Bug Websolder" changes positions, Special Summons Level 3 Insects from the hand and makes defense values 0 when used as Xyz material. "Digital Bug LEDybug" searches and allows Xyz monsters to draw cards whenever they destroy monsters in battle. "Digital Bug Cocoondenser" is primarily used as a monster revive.

Non-archetypal monsters include "Galaxy Worm" and "Galaxy Soldier", which provide easily summonable and self-searching Level 3/Level 5 monsters, "Honest" as surprising ATK boosts, "Bachibachibachi" to deal trample damage when used as Xyz material and "Mirror Ladybug" as an additional Special Summon.

The backrow is pretty straightforward: "Raigeki" and "Harpie's Feather Duster" clear front and backrow respectively, "Pot of Desires" is a useful draw option that does not really deal any damage to the overall consistency since every necessary card is at three, three "Bug Signal" allows your Xyz monster to dodge certain targeting effects and serves as the "Digital Bug" Rank-Up. Three copies of "Bug Emergency" can provide additional monsters for Xyz summons while also giving you an easier time summoning higher ranked monsters, three "Stumbling" trigger summoning effects of "Digital Bug" monsters while providing some field control and lastly two "Curse of Anubis" to have position changing on reaction. I also included "Solemn Strike" and "Solemn Warning" to potentially stop opposing plays.

The Extra Deck looks as follows: Three "Digital Bug Scaradiator" are absolutely necessary for climbing, beatdown and useful effect negation, two "Digital Bug Corebage" have grown on me since they do actually work quite well and one "Digital Bug Rhinosebus" as a finisher/beatdown option. Going into "Cyber Dragon Nova"/"Cyber Dragon Infinity" is a useful option that can be opted into rather often, "Inzektor Exa-Stag" is another Rank-Up option, while "Super Quantal Mech Beast Grampulse" is backrow removal. The deck included one "Number 20: Giga-Brilliant" which was a worst-case-scenario option, but after some feedback I included a copy of "Number 3: Cicada King" for being an absolute god-send that interacts with the "Digital Bug" archetype in various ways. The Link monsters consist of "Inzektor Picofalena" for small stat boosts, deck thinning and card draw, "Armillyre, the Starleader Dragon" for Special Summoning, "Topologic Trisbaena" as an improved backrow remover and "Saryuja Skull Dread" for all the useful things the monster does.

This "Digital Bug" build is certainly not the end-all-solution to what can be done with this archetype. However, I think this is a valid start. If you have ideas, feel free to comment, and if you want to read some more about the "Digital Bug" archetype you can visit the archetype analysis for them following this link: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2020/04/19/archetype-analysis-digital-bug/

deck_name: Kaiju Numeron (All or Nothing) Super Budget / Cheap
deck_excerpt: Big Boss Monster, going 1st, going 2nd? No Problem! Behold my Funny Numbers deck! I can assure you that they will die a quick overwhelming death ;) by
deck_description: Hello fellow Yu-Gi-Oh! Players. Did you just accidentally wanted to search for boring Meta decks but somehow got into my shitty side; then well what a welcome suprise. This deck is one of the simplest and funniest decks that you have ever seen. I have run a countless amounts of tests and I say that it is a deck that kills fast and efficient (if they don't play magic zylinder). But don't take my word. Take the words of our specialists called my friends (just kiddin, I have no friends ) and if you like it or support those braindead idea of mine, just leave a like or comment something for me to know so that I can post more of those abominations. And if you have questions about this deck, just comment bellow and i'll answer them as quick as possible.  How the deck works is simple. Even me monke brain understands this. Effektive Going 1st and 2nd, be assured that you're opponents will die as easy as possible by beating them with some 20k beatsticks for you being able to have lunch while otheres are sweating to win the match. And the best thing is that it is cheap. I made this deck as cheap as possible for you guys so that even the brokest of people (me included) can afford a competetive meta deck. I am talking to the brokest of the broke, the people that want to have the most fun with the least money to dab on the corpses of the meta players that paid hundreds and hundreds of dollars for crappy cardboard. *dab* And for the rich people out there that play gucci or louis vuitton there are some extra variants that you can play by putting your average op cards in it. Without further a do let's get right into it.  What's the strat?  Firstly be a gentleman and ask them whether they want going first or second. For you it doesn't matter but going 2nd is most of the time funnier because you can then run them over with your beatsticks.  Rules and Card effects are:  Try to get network resolving at all costs.  You can summon only one monster after network is resolved(but you can set 1 extra)  Always throw the kaiju at the opponents side before activating network.  You can only activate network if you control now monsters.  Psychic Fervor must be the last chain if not you'll die from Lp loss.  All your numerons cards get banished if they were not used for summon material in end phase.  Don't summon more monsters than neccessary to otk because of network and nibiru can screw you up longtime.  If you activate Kaiju slumber give yourself  the Light machine one first before giving the other one the normal light thunder one.  Going 1st you usually just summon 3 gates out of network to avoid nibiru and then go into zexal (a cheap trick for a cheap deck). and try to resolve gamma by negating a handtrap or activating Hope to draw additional cards to otk your opponents next turn with your drawn cards. Or just summon Inspector Boarder, set and pass. Works almost every time.  Going 2nd you usually make it a little bit more interesting. Firstly you have to get rid of the problematic monsters. If you drew a kaiju and your opponents summoned a monster just tribute the one that negates and then activate the eff of numeron network. No worries you'll draw it I made sure that this deck is filled of to the brimm with cards that search it and if not just resolve mystic mine (teeheehee). The strat is to bring out the gates because, if you haven't figured out yet. It's skystriker. ok ok I'll stop. Almost all of the monsters this deck has are light and machines what makes them perfect targets for having otk potential by activating Limiter removal, Psychic-Fervor, Honest or vic viper t301. The trick is to get the atk of your monsters on field as high as possible. The effect that boosts atk the least must be activated as the latest chain so that the atk will be as high as possible. And if you have problems getting over monsters or fear of backrow you can always use your extradeck. Mekk knight astram being a light with the eff to gain atk when attacking a special summoned monster (Kaiju *cough cough*) and Megaclops being machine make them viable with the doubling atk cards so that they will ensure you to kill them in one turn. And if you have kaiju slumber and two cards that boosts atk for example honest and limiter remover your monster's atk will get up to 13200atk which will roll over your opponents monster with ease.  The rest is self-explanatory.  Bonus for the ones reading this far:  You can spice this budget deck up by putting money cards in it to make it even better but more expensive. I would highly suggest putting magicians souls(with dogmatika fleur de lis) to get rid of unnecassary copys of network in your hand. This card will also allow you to play relinquished anima. Effect veiler although not expensive will also allow you to go into needlefiber and then selene and with the spells you discarded threw souls you'll be able to summon access code talker that is in itself a beast. A perfect addition to the main would also be forbidden droplet which in bonus of negation, reduces the opponents atk. Don't forget AA Zeus after overlaying into zexal and stunning your opponents. Guess what? Zeus is Light-Machine! And where should I begin with the side? Lightningstorm and so on and so on...  And if you came this far let me tell you a secret. Did you know that the Invoked Engines bossmonsters Invoked Mechaba is a Light Machine?!?! and that aleister has a effect that further doubles the atk? If you like me to show you the Invoked version of the deck let me know in the comments. Wish you a happy 2021!  Edit: HOLY FUCK! HOLY FUCK! I just realized now that Drytrons are LIGHT-MACHINE. How come I have just noticed yet. So now you can choose from Invoked, Numeron and Drytron-Light-Machine OTK! I'll probably make one Invoked and Drytron one sooner or later. I look forward to it. See ya!!!

deck_description: 40 card infernoble deck, using armageddon knight and plague spreader. Also using the deskbot auroadon combo. Cut the genba out, and the chalice to 2 bc i really wanted to make the profile 40 cards. The deck can play through certian handtraps like ash and imperm, but the deck loses to nibiru more often now. This isn't a problem because right now there is no deck that beats every hand trap. So if you are scarred to play any deck bc it loses to one hand trap you should just play a different game lol no side deck currently bc I have only played it online in singles. When i test it on remote duels and irl i will add a side deck. Also the deck has good one card/ two card combos that end on nasty boards, but also it has its own bricks, but any deck can brick. The bricks are not terrible you can play thru one brick bc plague spreader can put one card back into the deck, but drawing two of them makes it tougher, and you just need to use your brain to figure out a play. Also since i cut genba if you draw two of the one off equip spells you cannot do full combo, so adding genba is not a terrible idea if you want to have a back up play incase you do draw that. Also extra deck is pretty standard, except the abomination, i like it bc the charles abom synergy is ridilous but you can switch it for any other card maybe appolusa or accescode talker. Also the phantom in the side deck is for a hand loop combo i will show in a video. ALSO HAND TRAPS CAN BE CHANGED IF YOU OWN TTT PLAY IT INSTEAD OF LANCEA ITS BETTER BUT pick handtraps that fit ur meta and what decks you play against.

deck_name: TIER 1 Zoodiac Eldlich Dogmatika Deck + Combo Guide!
deck_excerpt: This deck and play both the 1st and seconds game, is very consistent and has only 1 brick in the form of driver.
deck_description: Hello and welcome to my Zoodiac build. Zoodiac-Zeus  just couldn't stand up to the metagame and it just couldn't play the slow game - something a control deck is supposed to be good at, it burns it resources too early. For this reason I am using both the Dogmatika and Eldlich cards to do this job. This deck and play both the 1st and seconds game, is very consistent and has only 1 brick in the form of driver. Going first it can set up a multiple negate board and going second Zeus can wreak everything. This deck can end on Drident, 2 pops, a monster negate and multiple backrow going first. Going second you can make Zeus with multiple materials, and also use cards like gamma to counter VFD and use golden lord as removal. This deck is a solid pick for the metagame and can also counter most meta decks. The side deck was designed to answer all the top tier meta decks as of now. Also make sure to answer the poll question down below!   For in in depth deck explanation and combo tutorial check out my youtube video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VFtcBVAZxGo&t=8s   Thanks and I'll see you next time! :D

deck_excerpt: Invoked Volcanics, which is a mix between burn/beatdown.
deck_description: So, here’s another cursed deck i’ve made. This time, Invoked Volcanics, even though they have no synergy and this deck makes no fucking sense. You’re welcome, fuckers. This guide took me, like, two days, and i’m exhausted and i want to die. Also, credit to my boy RATA for his vid that helped me with this.                                         Deck guide 3x Rocket- Rocket is a key card of the deck, as it searches the Accelerator spell/trap line up for your plays, as the Accelators are essential. Although, it does take up the summon which you would normally like to use for Aleister, so. 3x Scattershot- Scattershot gives a miniscule amount of burn damage to the opponent, although that’s not the most important part of Scattershot. Scattershot, when it’s sent to the grave, sends 2 more copies of Scattershot to the grave, which inflict burn 500 more burn damage. This stacks up to 1500, which is pretty meaty, and sets up the grave for more plays. 3x Shell- Shell is another important card for the deck, as you want to shit it out to the grave to infict a tiny amount of burn from the guns. Afterwards, you’ll want to use Shell’s effect to get more Shells, providing a ton of more fodder to shoot off with the guns. 2x Counter- Counter is a pretty nice card as a surprise against the opponent, as you can dump it and the opponent’ll probably not read it and forget about it. When they swing in on you, you can use Counter to inflict a fuck ton of burn damage considering how high the modern stats are. Although, Counter is mandatory, so it can be creeped out with the smallest monster on the opponent’s board, so remember that. 2x Agnizinmaud- However you spell it, the True King thingy is really good at getting a body on board and monsters in the grave. It can get itself onto the board without taking up the normal summon, which is great for this deck as it can struggle to get large bodies on board. Additionally, he props the effects of your Volcanics, since he destroys them (which sends them to the grave) for cost. Additionally, on summon, he gets non-targeting banishing, which is amazing. 3x Royal Firestorm Guards- Royal Firestorm Guards mainly serve to recycle your resources and is your main source of draw power. You constantly shit out monsters non-stop into the grave, so Firestorm recycles them for later plays, and gives you a  great draw 2 to extend your plays. Firestorm does take up your normal summon though, so you do have to be careful with it and Aleister. 3x Aleister- Aleister is a key part of the Invoked engine, as it’s the main material of all of the Invoked fusions. Additionally, you mainly want to normal summon it if you don’t have an Invocation in hand already, so you can search invocation. Although, if you did draw into Invocation, you don’t need to normal summon Aleister, leaving your normal summon free for Rocket and Firestorm. Aleister can be bricky sometimes, but is worth it because of the strength of the Invoked engine. 3x Gamma- Gamma is the deck’s main handtrap, as it’s an omni-negate for monsters. Gamma is really important in the current meta as it can negate VFD and the such, which is insanely important in the current meta for, y’know, not dying. Gamma also gets a body on board. The main problem of Gamma is that it requires a brick just to use it,  which is a pain in the ass. 1x Driver- Driver is, basically a shitty garnet thats just for Gamma. You want to keep it in the deck, as it’s a pain in the ass to draw into. 2x Blaze Accelerator- Blaze Accelerator isn’t very good due to how restrictive it is, meaning you’ll want to just use it and then send it to the grave in order to activate  Tri-Blaze. Blaze Accelerator can still be used in emergency situations, though. 2x Tri-Blaze- Tri-Blaze is mainly used to send Blaze, and then activate it. Tri-Blaze is great for filling up your grave with Pyro’s (with way less restrictions than Blaze), and it gives non-targeting destruction. It also gives a small amount of burn damage, but coupled with Scattershot it comes to 2000, which is a big number for burn. 3x Invocation- Invocation is an amazing card for the Invocation engine, as you can use monsters from your hand, graveyard, or the opponent’s grave. This is great, as you can fill up the grave with more Volcanics if you’re making a Purgatrio, or you can make literally anything else using the opponent’s bullshit. 2x Meltdown- Meltdown searches Aleister whenever you need it, although i’ve found in playtesting that you rarely need Meltdown due to the three of Aleister, so I cut Meltdown down to 2. Meltdown also gives your fusion summons protection, but thats not as notable. 3x Foolish Burial Goods- Foolish Burial Goods is mainly used to send Reload to the grave, for it’s great grave effect. 1x Foolish Burial- Foolish Burial is mainly used for sending shit like Scattershot to the grave in order to activate their effects, and it sends them for no cost, and without the iffy requirements of stuff like the Blaze Accelerators. 1x Instant Fusion- Instant Fusion is mainly used for getting out Raidjin, so you can flip down the opponent’s main source of negates to either A) Bait out their negate, or B) completely rid the negates. 3x Reload- Reload’s on field effect effect is fairly solid, as it allows you to ditch a Volcanic (triggering their GY effect and filling up the GY), and draw 1, which is amazing for generating tons of advantage. Due to this being a trap, though, this is insanely slow and annoying to use. It’s grave effect is what is special about Reload, though. You’re able to banish Reload from the grave to send a Volcanic from d e c k, which is amazing, as you don’t need to use your hand. This is great, as it fills up your grave and triggers things like Scattershot without having to use resources from your precious hand. The extra deck 2x Caliga- Caliga is a great floodgate to end the turn off of on, as you can pass with it and make sure the opponent can’t rebuild their board. Due to how common the Dark attribute is on a ton of decks, it’s fairly easy to make it with the opponent’s cards. 1x Raidjin- Raidjin is mainly summoned off of Instant Fusion, and it’s used to bait out negates, since you can summon it and attempt to flip down the opponent’s negation boss monster. They’ll be forced to either have it flip down, or use their negate on Raidjin, which can save your plays. 3x Purgatrio- Purgatrio is the deck’s main Invoked monster, as since you mainly use  Fire monsters, you can get out Purg consistenstenly. Purgatrio is basically a big, strong beater, and a fun card in general to use. 1x Cocytus- Cocytus is mainly used for just, being a big wall that can lightly poke at the opponent sometimes. Cocytus is rarely summoned, only in certain match ups or situations. 2x Augo- Augo is mainly a large body mid- to late game, as you can get some removal with it and then it grows to be a big beater, which is great for closing off games. 3x Mechaba- Mechaba is another amazing monster in the deck, as it’s the deck’s main source of negations. Mechaba also sends cards from your hand directly to the grave, which triggers the effects of the Volcanics, making Mechaba stack up value. 3x Elysium- Elysium is mainly just a big boss monster for late game, as it’s a large 32k beater that can provide non-targeting banishing removal, which is amazing in the current meta. The side deck 3x Volcanic Queen- Volcanic Queen is a great card, as it’s basically a kaiju with extra effects. While it’s on the opponent’s field, it forces them to tribute monsters or take 1000 damage, which is great for the Volcanic playstyle. It’s mainly just in the side due to certain match ups and such. 3x Ash- Ash, you know what Ash does. It’s in the side deck because there was no space in the main. 3x D.D Crow- See above. 3x Lightning Storm- Lightning Storm is a great card for clearing fields when going 2nd. 3x Imperm- Imperm is mainly used for negating scary monsters when going 2nd. Playing guide So, this is mainly a going second burn deck. You’ll want to opt to go second, as this deck dies going first. Immediately activate your Blaze Accelerators, so you can send your Volcanics to clear the opponent’s field and inflict a ton of burn damage (if you’re using Scattershot.) You’ll also want to use your normal summon after that, either normal summoning Rocket to fill the gaps in your hand, or Aleister to nab you a Invocation. Then, you’ll want to turbo into either Purgatrio or  Mechaba, and hopefully use Reload for more effects. From there, swing in with Purg or whichever fusion you got, and if the game wasn’t closed off in that turn, finish burning them to death on turn 2. Note: A Mystic Mine package might be a nice tech choice, although I haven’t tried that out. Any suggestions or shit like that is appreciated. Have a good day : )

deck_excerpt: Shaddoll deck with Elemental Hero engine
deck_description: So this deck is very much a work in progress, but it's been promising enough that I wanted to post about it.  The basic concept is that Blazeman is a normal summon that allows you to grab a fusion spell, similar to how Alesiter can help bolster the consistency of Shaddoll in the Invoked variant. Blazeman can also turn into either a Light or Water attribute in this deck, making him a genuine swiss army knife for the Shaddoll archetype. There has been some thought to adding Shadowmist as well to give access to the Dark attribute, but it felt like too much of a brick.  Liquidman and Honest Neos let you turn your Emergency Call into different attributes, as well as having useful effects of their own. The synergy between Liquidman and the Shaddolls is quite good. Neos is mostly just a tutor target, but he can be useful at cracking over your opponents Windas or whatnot with Blazeman or Liquidman.  Everything else is pretty standard Shaddoll. We have the full Shaddoll combo package as well as some tech like Gameceil (who also doubles as an outlet for Absolute Zero). The extra deck could probably be better optimized, this is just what I've landed on for now.  Any feedback is appreciated!

deck_excerpt: Look at all these scrubs ending their turn with cards in hand
deck_description:
Infernity cannot access lots of the generic meta staples lots of other decks can, mainly hand traps. But, due to a number of missing hard once-per-turns, there is a lot of room for creativity. From crazy boards full of negates to full-out hand loops, Infernity has a lot of potential. Combo So Infernity may seem a bit complicated to the average player. Most Infernity lists you see are probably going to look a lot different than this one, mainly because they have different end-goals than my list. But before you can begin to understand this list, you must know the combo. If you have any suggestions on how I could improve this combo, tell me in the comments. Do note that this deck does require a bit of a brain. Depending on your opening hand and Saryuja draws, you may need to adjust the combo as you go. So the beginning is non-linear. The first thing you need to do is get both Infernity Archfiend and Infernity Necromancer in the GY. Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss does a very good job at helping out at this, so you'll typically have him on-field as well by the time the combo starts. Once you have gotten the set-up, you need to hope that you opened one of the following cards: Monster Reborn, World Legacy Succession, Charge into a Dark World, and/or ZERO-MAX. These reborn cards are essential to starting up the combo. If anyone knows of any other reborn cards the deck can use (note we can't use stuff like Living Fossil because we need the monster to be able to activate its effect and go back to the GY) then please tell me in the comments. Now with that out of the way, let's get into the actual combo.
  1. Revive Necromancer with a reborn card, revive Archfiend from Nerco's effect
  2. Search Infernity Patriarch, summoning him from hand
  3. Overlay into Number 60: Dugares the Timeless using Archfiend and Patriarch
  4. Revive Archfiend, search Infernity Launcher
  5. Activate Launcher, but do not use its effect yet
  6. Make a 4-mat Saryuja Skull Dread
  7. Now, to continue you are going to hope that you draw into another reborn card. Thankfully, with all of the searching and milling you have already done, you have a high chance of nabbing one of the 10 in your deck. This reliance on reborn cards is one of the reasons the deck still needs more support. However, the odds are in your favor
  8. Revive Necro, bring back Archfiend, and search Infernity Avenger
  9. Summon Avenger through Saryuja's effect
  10. Make Saryuja again, grab another reborn
  11. Bring back Necro, Necro revives Archfiend, search Infernity Mirage
  12. Summon Mirage through Saryuja, tributing him for Avenger + Patriarch
  13. Make Hundred Eyes Dragon using Avenger, Archfiend, and Necro
  14. Banish Mirage for Hundred Eyes effect, tributing Hundred for Necro and Avenger
  15. Necro for Archfiend, search Infernity Barrier 1
  16. Using Saryuja and Avenger, make Crystron Halqifibrax for Infernity Wildcat
  17. Overlay Wildcat and Necro into Leviair the Sea Dragon, bring back Mirage
  18. Use Sea Dragon, Patriarch, Archfiend, and Noodle for Saryuja (what you draw here doesn't really matter. If you get lucky and get another reborn card/extender you may be able to add another negate to your end board)
  19. Tribute Mirage for Avenger and Necro, Necro for Archfiend, search Barrier 2
  20. Make Hundred again using Avenger, Necro, and Archfiend
  21. Hundred Eyes banishing Mirage, tributing him to summon Avenger and Necro
  22. Necro for Wildcat, make Sea Dragon, detaching Necro for Mirage
  23. Mirage for Nerco and Avenger, Necro for Archfiend
  24. Search Necro 2
  25. Saryuja to summon Necro 2 from hand
  26. Archfiend, Necro 1 (the one that already used its effect/the one you didn't just search), Sea Dragon, and Saryuja for Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess
  27. Necro 2 brings back Archfiend, search Barrier 3, use them and Avenger to make Borreload Savage Dragon, attaching Saryuja. While we could make a Void Ogre Dragon here, there isn't much of a need as Savage does everything he does. You may argue that Void Ogre destroys, but the ruling is if you negate the activation of a Spell/Trap, then the card is sent to the GY by game mechanic even if it wasn't destroyed. And since this is inferring you are going first, as the deck does going second, your opponent shouldn't have any cards on the field to begin with
  28. Send Launcher to the GY for Necro 1 and Necro 2, Necro 1 for Avenger, making Herald of the Arc Light, and Necro 2 for Wildcat, making Infernity Doom Archfiend (must be in ATK Position to make your 3 Barriers live)
Funny enough, I think that if all of these cards were legal in Master Rule 4, the entire combo would still be possible (correct me if I'm wrong). Not that it means much, just thought it was interesting. (Note that with an extra extender, you may be able to make that same board, but with a Void Ogre Dragon alongside it.) Ratios So a basic overview of the ratios, I won't go into full detail, just a quick brush over. So excluding the combo pieces above, we have tons of triple-axis tools, because we really need to make Cherubini. You may have noticed Performapal Hip Hippo. That is for our secret meta-destroying spice, Super Hippo Carnival. An E-Tele that can summon from hand, deck, or GY, meaning Hip Hippo is never a garnet, just a dead draw, and in addition to a lack of a once-per-turn clause allows you to activate all three copies in the duel, sometimes in the same turn. That should be it for the monsters. The only traps of the deck are searchable during the combo so that just leaves the spell cards. Fossil Dig, Void Apocalypse, and Super Hippo Carnival all help in making Cherubini. Launcher is arguably the strongest card in your deck, searchable in the combo. And the rest is your reborn cards which are essential to the combo. Now let's talk about the Extra Deck. Everything except your bosses, Savage, Ogre, Herald, and Apollousa is set in stone. Unless you come up with a different combo, those bosses are the only things you can change. If you can think of anything better than these bosses (2 Level 8 Synchros, a Level 4 Synchro, and a Link-4 for going first) tell me in the comments. Strengths & Flaws So the endboard looked pretty good. Infernity is a really fun deck to play, and there are several different combo lines you could adapt. Typically, your end board is essentially an FTK. Usually, Infernity is used as a board-building monstrosity. But don't worry, it isn't unbeatable. First of all, going second is almost a death sentence. Secondly, hand traps hurt. If your opponent fires them too early before the combo began, then you may stand a chance depending on the number of extenders you have available. But if they hit you during the combo, then you are kind of dead. Another big thing is consistency, which is why I am considering Performapal Popperup, for the consistency boost, GY set-up, and the ability to bait hand traps such as Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. As stated earlier, this deck struggles at using the meta generic staples that most other decks can. The only hand traps you can really run are sided in for when you know you are going second, or Infinite Impermanence for its ability to be set and out of your hand. Other than that, you are out of luck. Lastly, the end board isn't unbeatable. Spell Speed 4 effects such as Super Polymerization and Forbidden Droplet work great against your deck. The ability to simply get rid of the Attack Position Infernirty (whether through battle or those SS4 effects) on your to invalidate your Barriers and make your board worthless through a single Dark Ruler No More. But despite these flaws, I highly recommend the deck for anyone interested. Lots of rogue decks suffer these same weaknesses, so it shouldn't be news to most people (unless you only ever play what's meta for the current format, and never touch anything below that: which is fine too, I guess). Banlist & Support So, as you may know, Infernity Archfiend and Infernity Launcher are both limited. Archfiend had literally no reason to stay on the list, been of he came to 3 you may run a second for stuff like D.D. Crow (maybe you would put in the side?). But in reality, Archfiend to 3 wouldn't really do anything. Launcher on the other hand would raise the ceiling of the deck to hand loop 5 and sit behind 3 omni-negates, very consistently and with a lot of resilience against several hand traps, with the exception of D.D. Crow and Droll & Lock Bird. Those 2 can stop you in your tracks. What about the support? You may have noticed that Infernity Conjurer and Infernity Suppression are very solid cards. Why don't we run them? We don't run them because we don't run enough Infernity cards. That's right. We don't have enough Infernoty cards in an Infernity deck. We don't have enough play starters for either, something the new support did not give us. By the time Suppression is live, you are already performing the combo, where it's anti-hand trap prowess would be too late. Hopefully, Konami gives the archetype more support in the near future so that we can use some of these cards to the fullest. Closing Remarks Well done for reading this far (considering that you are a Yu-Gi-Oh player, and most of the player base is semi-illiterate). If you have any suggestions, tell me in the comments section. The side deck is currently just a bunch of ideas I want to test out. So I'll close off with this:
  • I will be updating my horrible Eldlich-Nordic into something that has actual synergy, Tri-Brigade Nordic. That should be done in the near future.
  • I will also be updating my Plunder list to include combos involving Ravenwing, the Plunder Patroll Pilot, and a few changes to the list.
  • Lastly, I will release a Witchcrafter list in the near future, so be on the look out for that.

deck_excerpt: Invoked Myutants, more designed for a slow ass beat down focus.
deck_description: Like normal, i'm trying to mash Invokeds into something because I love Invokeds. Myutants don't work as well with Invokeds as Dragonmaids did, but they still do work fairly well. They have a few ranging attributes to use, and Invocation banishes cards, providing more banish fodder. Deck list time. 2x Arsenal- too bricky at 3. Another one of the, like, weird evolved forms that I run at 2. Pretty good in the current meta, considering how it can dodge pog blade, imperm, and the cringe Eldlich trap line up, making Arsenal pretty solid to leave on the field. 2x Mist- i'm seeing a patttern here. I run all the weird evolved forms at 2. Mist gives instant advantage by banishing a card to draw 2 when your opponent activates a effect, which can easily turn into a plus 3 in the right situation.  While it's a bit slow, it's still a solid source of draw power. 2x Beast- Beast is solid. Can't be targeted by monster effects, which dodges Dragoon, Borreload, etc, which is great in the current meta Also negates spell cards by banishing cards, so it gathers advantage and can easily negate key points of the opponent's combo. 3x Aleister- Mandatory for the Invoked engine. Great searcher as well. It takes up a normal summon (sometimes), which can clash with the Myutants (sometimes), but if you open Invocation you don't even need to normal it. Aleister leads to a ton of strong fusions, namely Mechaba for a source of strong negates. 1x GB-88- I personally run 88 at  1, since it's effect to special summon it is awkward and situational and can brick easily depending on the situation. Works well with Cry though. It's also fairly good late game recovery, as if it's summoned during the opponent's turn, it can be tributed to special a banished level 8 Myutant, which is great for recovering advantage and building your board. 3x ST-46- ST-46 is generally a reliable searcher for the Myutants, as it searches a spell/trap on summon.  If you need fusion, you can get a fusion, you can get a cry, etc. This is great for filling in the gaps in your hand and extending your plays. ST-46 also helps greatly with field swarming, as you can tribute it and banish a monster/spell/trap to special a corresponding level 8 Myutant from hand or deck, so that's great for field swarming and building up a strong board. 3x M-05- M-05 searches out all of the Myutant monsters, which is great for also filling in the gaps in your hand and extending your plays greatly, so you can build a strong board. M-05 also has the same secondary effect as ST-46, making it so you can get out two Level 8's to make a huge board. 3x Ash Blossom- ez negate 2x Ghost Ogre- ez destruction 1x Cyberstien- This deck doesn't use it's normal summon a ton, so if you don't need to normal summon an Aleister at the moment, you can normal summon a Cyberstein to cheat out Ultimus without the entire convuluted Cry process.  Banish/fusion fodder otherwise. 3x Magical Meltdown- Meltdown helps a lot with consistency, as you can search out Aleister if you need one. It also gives you some heavy protection onto the fusion summons, avoiding making the fusion summons into a chokepoint. 3x Myutant Evolution Lab- Da archtypel field spell. Evo lab provides an easy special summon that can free up your normal summon for Aleister or Cyber-Stein, which is great for this deck, and a small attack boost. 3x Invocation- Invocation is an amazing card, as it can use nearly any monster for the fusion, leading into tons of strong monsters like Mechaba. Additionally, this provides a ton of banish fodder, as it banishes Aleister and such. 3x Myutant Fusion- Myutant Fusion is the main archetypal fusion spell, as it allows you to provide a ton of banish fodder to go into your fusions. Additionally, if the opponent's activated a hand trap this turn (which they most likely will have considering the current game), you can banish cards from Deck or GY as well, which is amazing for turboing out fusions.The only bad part of Fusion is that it has a retarded hard once per turn on it, making it a bit annoying to use. 1x Terraforming- Terraforming is mainly used for searching out whichever field spell you need at the time, Meltdown or Evo lab. Although, if you don't need either, you can also use Terraforming to bait out hand traps. 1x Set Rotation- Set Rotation is mainly used to set your Meltdowns and Evo Lab to both player's fields (after you use the field spell plays), which is great for halting a ton of field spell relient decks. 3x Myutant Cry- Cry is amazing for getting out Ultimus on the opponent's turn if you couldn't use Fusion, as it allows you to access a ton of different points for the fusion- Banished cards (which you should have a lot of), GY, and field, so you can easily make a huge Ultimus during the opponent's turn for a ton of interruption. Although, like Fusion, Cry has a hard once per turn, meaning no double Ultimus boards that easy. 3x Trap Trick-Trap Trick is a great card for consistency, as it allows you to search out Cry easily, improving the consistency in "turboing" out Ultimus greatly. Extra deck 3x Ultimus- Ultimus is generally a huge beater, as 35k is a greatly above average stat line. Additionally, it has a great negate that provides more banish fodder, and generates advantage on destruction. 2x Mechaba- Mechaba is a great source of negates for the deck, as it can negate literally anything and provides a ton of graveyard set up for Cry later on. 3x Synthethis- Synethethis gives a fairly nice pop on summon, although it might not be of use, considering this is a going 1st deck. Syneththis also provides a nice pseudo-negate built in, generally a solid monster to "rank up" into Ultimus by fusing it during the opponent's turn, for heavy interruption. 1x Magellanica- Maggeaicialli or however you spell it is generally just a big 3k beater that helps to close off the game in mid to late game. 2x Purgatrio- Another solid beater, Purg grows to big stats to punish swarm decks and can punish things like Guru control with it's piercing damage. 2x Cocytus- Cocytus is mainly just a large, shitty wall, that can poke at the opponent and stall until you get into a better position. 1x Raijin- Built in book of moon, helps to beat over problem monsters. It can also be used to bait out negates, as you can attempt to flip over a negate monster like Borreload. Either they're forced to use up their negate on Raidjin, or have to let it go. 1x Caliga- god i love floodgates Playing guide This won't be super in depth or anything. I've done a bit of play testing, and my main strategy is fairly simple.  If you don't have an Aleitser, activate Meltdown to search one. If you already have one, Meltdown is just usable for Set Rotation. If you didn't activate Meltdown, or after activating Meltdown, activate Evo lab to special summon a monster. Search Evo with terraforming if you don't already have it.  Tribute the small special summoned Myutant (the one that's in the cage) to search either a monster or a spell, while also providing more banish fodder. Afterwards, fusion summon Synthethis using Myutant Fusion, or search a Fusion using 46 if you don't already have one. After fusion summoning Synthethis, use Invocation to get out whatever Invoked fits the current moment attribute wise. Pass turn. During your opponent's turn, activate Cry and use Synthethis to get out Ultimus much easier. Note: I didn't mention it, but throughout this, you can normal summon Cyber Stein or Aleister if neccesary. Cyber Stein is fantastic for cheating out Ultimus, or if you already have Ultimus, you can use it to get out an extra Ultimus or a Synthethis. also note you'll want to go first so you can set up Cry with Trap Trick to get into Ultimus easier. Any feedback or thoughts is appreciated in the comments. Thanks for reading this, have a good day.

deck_excerpt: A fun Danger! Dark World variant with some OTK and lockdown potential
deck_description:
I love the concept of the Danger! Dark World deck and decided to try my hand at building my own version of it. Got some ideas from this deck, mainly the ideas for some of the extra deck setups: https://ygoprodeck.com/dark-world-danger-december-2020/ I also wanted to add an explanation of why I included each card for both your purposes if you wanna use/modify this and my own if you'd like to give me some feedback with my reasonings in mind. This is my first time posting a deck I built so if you have any suggestions or critiques let me know! :D Monsters:
  • 2x Beiige: I’ve seen other decks run a single Beiige and work well, but I think this setup in particular has some really good Beiige synergy down the line, particularly with Charge Into a Dark World for setting up your Rank 4 XYZ summon (Utopia line) or the Knightmare link monsters to start breaking your opponent’s board
  • 3x Broww: A staple here, just gives you more cards when he’s discarded, which is especially nice when done via Dark Deal to get the extra card
  • 3x Snoww: Your Dark World searcher, can also disrupt your opponent’s GY when paired with Dark Deal which is useful against GY combo-oriented decks like Thunder or Chaos
  • 3x Grapha: Used to run 2, but his effect is just too powerful and his ability to cycle himself out of the GY while also giving you another use of a Dark World’s discard effect is way too good to pass up on. GY cycling in particular gives him a lot of use bringing out the powerful Rank 8 XYZ summons (of which there are plenty to choose from), giving him even more utility here
  • 3x Bigfoot: Excellent all around with board breaking, Level 8 synergy with Trade-In, and just being an easy-to-summon powerhouse at 3k attack. Obvious pick for playsetting
  • 3x Chupacabra: A little less obvious of a playset pick, but I think Chupacabra synergizes more with this deck than others I’ve seen of this type given that he’s a Fiend and can be pulled back from the grave OR discarded with Charge, giving you an additional avenue of firing off his powerful GY effect.
  • 3x Mothman: Just lets you get more cards and discard effects, easy playset
  • 1x Nessie: Either a powerful defender, link fodder, or more discard effects
  • 1x Ogopogo: This might seem like a weird pick to only run 1 of given how many Rank 8 XYZs I’m running, but I think keeping in the traps as protection for going first is worth the trade-off. Ogopogo is here particularly to synergize with Danger! Response Team, since its GY effect lets you get both a Danger! discard effect and an extra draw
  • 3x Thunderbird: Basically the same as Bigfoot without being as big of a powerhouse and board breaking in a different way, still an easy playset pick
  • 1x Jackalope: Don’t know if I need to explain this one, excellent for grabbing XYZ or link material
  • 1x Tsuchinoko: Same as Jackalope but he uses himself, also he’s a fat snake. Easy include for that alone
Spells:
  • 1x Card Destruction: Any Danger! Dark World deck should be playing this card
  • 2x Charge Into a Dark World: I alluded to it before but this card has great synergy with both Beiige and Chupacabra, and Skull Meister if you side him in. Since it doesn’t specify Dark World, you can use it with any Fiend, letting you get at least one special summon and whatever discard effect you want. It unfortunately doesn’t synergize with other Danger! monsters besides Chupacabra, but I think it provides enough reliable XYZ or link setup to be worth it
  • 1x Danger! Response Team: Works incredible well with Ogopogo and lets you recycle it into the deck while drawing a card and getting another Danger! discard effect. Also just has a really good primary effect if you need to get rid of an opponent’s targetable monster that can’t be destroyed by effects or is too strong for your hand to deal with
  • 1x Pot of Avarice: Easy pick with so many monster discards
  • 2x Super Poly: Opponent board breaking, discard effect (only for Danger! monsters since it discards as cost), getting Starving Venom or Mudragon. What’s not to love here?
  • 3x Trade-In: I play a lot of good Level 8s here with strong discard effects, so this is a great pick for both getting those powerful effects and getting more cards to work with
Traps:
  • 2x Dark Deal: I don’t see this card too often in these decks and I think it should be. The main weakness of a lot of Danger! Dark World decks is that they’re really bad at going first, but this card helps mitigate that by denying the opponent a normal Spell card while giving you access to the more powerful discard effects, like getting two cards from Broww or breaking GY monster combos with Snoww
  • 1x Eradicator Epidemic Virus: Another way to stave off the problems with going first, this card actually has great synergy with Grapha. Since Grapha can bring himself back from the GY and recycle Dark World discard effects simultaneously, he’s the obvious pick for EEV’s tribute cost. I’ve won entire duels with this card alone and I think it puts in the work to justify being here
Extra:
  • Mudragon: Super Poly target, lets you stave off targeting enemy effects when you change him to Dark
  • Starving Venom Fusion Dragon: The staple Super Poly target
  • Dingirsu: Really powerful Rank 8, excellent both on his own and as a setup into Seven Sins. Gets removal when he’s first summoned that avoids enemy effects that happen on destruction and has built-in survival if you’re planning to use him on his own
  • Number 84: Pain Gainer: Not much to talk about with him besides being ranking material into Seven Sins
  • Number 77: Seven Sins: Incredible beatstick that can just wipe an opponent’s entire field. Gets around cards that can’t be destroyed or targeted since it’s a non-targeting banish and will have plenty of survival if you didn’t use any of Dingirsu or Pain Gainer’s material effects. The only issue is he’ll need to stay on the field for a turn to use his banish effect, since he can’t use it turn one if he’s summoned through rank-up, but that’s not too tough since his survival effect isn’t once per turn and he’ll have anywhere from 1-4 uses of it
  • Number 97: Draglubion: This guy’s your setup into the OTK if you can get it. Use him to special summon Number 100 with Number C92 as its material and fire off 100’s effect for a min. 9k attacker. If the combo gets disrupted or you can’t quite get the OTK off, Draglubion also works as Pain Gainer->Seven Sins fodder if he can survive a turn after using his effect
  • Number 100: Numeron Dragon: The pick you’ll probably want for Draglubion’s special summon, enables quick OTKs especially if you have more than just Draglubion on the field (like if you got Seven Sins or the Rank 4 setup earlier), can swing over just about any monster your opponent can summon, very strong pick overall
  • Number C92: Heart-eartH Chaos Dragon: Material to attach to Number 100 with Draglubion. His effect doesn’t really work unless he has the specific monster listed on his card as material, so the only thing he’s good for being summoned on his own is he’s unable to be destroyed by battle and he makes your monsters siphon LP when they do battle damage. If your opponent’s run out of other removal options or you’re super low on LP and can get some good hits in this might not be the worst pick, but if you can get good hits in you’re probably in a better spot to just win with Number 100
  • Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy: Another possible pick for Draglubion, his lockdown on enemy Spell cards is insanely effective and makes him a great choice if you can’t get the OTK or see your opponent has some reliance on Spell cards. He can also change an opponent’s attack target, which makes him good at keeping a weaker field member alive like a Level 4 you need a turn to XYZ
  • Utopia/Utopia Prime/Utopia the Lightning: The Rank 4 line I use, this is an incredibly strong setup that can easily swing over whatever your opponent might have. Lightning’s effect actually makes it a Dragoon counter since your opponent can’t use effects until the end of the Damage Step, so they can’t negate Lightning’s jump to 5000 ATK. A great powerhouse that’s incredibly easy to set up with this deck
  • Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess: This card is a personal favorite of mine. Getting Apollousa and Hope Harbinger out on the field at the same time is an incredibly effective lockdown on your opponent. Her negates are limited based on how many materials you use to summon her, which can be annoying if your opponent has many ways to lead into their combos, but overall she’s still a very strong pick
  • Knightmare Phoenix: Easy to summon, Spell/Trap removal, and works as an engine for discard effects from your Main Deck monsters
  • Knightmare Unicorn: Also easy to summon and helps get discard effects, but has the added bonus of being non-destructive removal
Side:
  • 3x Skull Meister: GY effects are very strong in YGO today, so Skull Meister is great at staving off things like “when this card is destroyed” effects and blocking your opponent’s combos. Also has good inherent synergy with this deck by being a Level 4 Fiend, meaning he can do his thing as a handtrap and then be recovered by Charge to use as link/XYZ fodder
  • 3x Sphere Mode: Enemy board removal, very good if your opponent has strong lockdown combos that require them to have a bunch of monsters on the field (something like Dragoon, Hope Harbinger, and Apollousa)
  • 3x Twin Twisters: Spell/Trap removal that also triggers Danger! monster effects by discarding them
  • 3x Infinite Impermanence: Just one of the best handtraps overall imo
  • Galaxy Eyes line: This is another Rank 8 XYZ setup you can use in place of the Dragons or Seven Sins (or the link monsters if you wanna go all in on XYZ), it just felt like overkill to include all three of these in the Extra Deck when there’s a good chance the duel will be over before you can see all three or even two of the combos. The Galaxy-Eyes setup is very powerful though and makes a strong argument for replacing one of the others, this one is just personal preference mostly

deck_excerpt: Sky strikers+There can be  only on= Perfect stall deck
deck_description: So, guess what? It’s Sky Striker back again.This is one of my favorite decks from  all time , so much so that it deserves an entire explanation about how and why I built it this way. So let’s get it started.   First of all: Why sky striker?        Sky striker was  one of the best decks in Yu-Gi-OH!  history, so much so that it stays one of the best decks of the past 2 years formats , even with severe hits on the banlist ( Sky Striker Mecha Modules - Multirole and Sky Striker Ace - Kagari limited, semi-limited and after limited  Sky Striker Mecha - Widow Anchor). However its reign ended with the  April1st 2020 banlist, when it was banned now infamous Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage!, the heart and soul of the deck.  After that  the  Sky Striker deck vanished from the top tier contenders being now on a mere rogue  deck.      But now it’s the time. The time for Sky Striker  to shine once more, Sky Striker Mecha - Widow Anchor and Sky Striker Ace - Kagari are at 3 and the today format ruled by virtual world, zoo eldlich, dino and others monstrosities will see the power of the anime colegial girls once more.   Disclaimers      When I try to build a deck I like to use cards that I already have,thus I rarely have the new staples for exemple. So the majority of cards that you’ll see can be considered a budget option for certain cards, in other words no Access code talker =/.    Starters 3x Sky Striker Ace - Raye: This cute girl or your  main starter. She can bring almost every   sky striker monster in your extra deck and makes a good protection for your Links sky striker monsters against destruction, 'cause Raye can bring herself from the GY and link again in another sky striker.    2x Sky Striker Ace - Roze : The fearson antagonist of Raye,  Roze can be another great starter for the sky striker link play. The effect that she can be summoned with another sky striker is good, but the effect that she returns to the field when an opponent's monster is removed from the extra monster zone is beyond insane, additionally can also negate the effect of another opponent's monster. This card is insane.    1x Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones :  another way to summon the links monster. Furthermore it can be used for other combos  utilizing link-2 monsters like I:P Masquerena , Knightmare Phoenix or Sky Striker Ace - Zeke.    1x Reinforcement of the army : search Raye of Roze depending on your needs.   Pseudo Starters   They’re considered startartes only if certain conditions are fulfilled (combination  with  other specific cards, luck in a draw, etc.)   3x Sky Striker Airspace - Area Zero + 1x Sky Striker Mecha Modules - Multirole:  Area zero can dig more in your deck while  finding a copy of the sky striker monster or a sky striker spell. alternaly , you can use  Multirole to pop Are zero and get a free summon of Roze or Raye.   Extenders   3x Sky Striker Airspace - Area Zero:  Explained above.   1x Terraforming:  Search  Sky Striker Airspace - Area Zero to help in your plays.   1x Foolish Burial Goods:  It can send any spell of your deck  to GY that later can be  recovered  with  Sky Striker Ace - Kagari or  ( for further plays) you can send Metalfoes Fusion.   1x Metalfoes Fusion : its main goal is to send to Gy  or by the effect of Foolish burial goods or the main target for Sky Striker Airspace - Area Zero or Sky Striker Mecha Modules - Multirole. The effect of drawing again is always welcome.   1x Upstart Goblin:  Draw a card, nothing to explain.   3x Pot of Desire: It’s a high risk card ‘cause you can lose so many goods cards with this card, but at the same time I found sky strikers kind of brick  after the Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage! ban , thus  this card can fix your hand with you needed.   1x Pot of Avarice: Face it, you will send a lot of monsters to GY  so this card can recover some of this card and help with the card advantage.   1x Sky Striker Mecha Modules - Multirole: This card shines with your second effect to use  every Sky Striker spell … all over again. Insane and deserve to be limited   2x Sky Striker Ace - Hayate: She is amazing and  the perfect monster to stall your opponent with Mystic mine. She can also send a sky striker spell to late recovery with Sky Striker Ace - Kagari.   3x Sky Striker Ace - Kagari: The effect to add to your hand any sky striker spell is outrageous. Cycle spell, recover spell that was negated, search cards in conjunction with Sky Striker Ace - Hayate… this card does so much for one card that deserves the time that was banned.   3x Sky Striker Ace - Shizuku: This is your primally way to get the spell that you wanted, too bad it only in you final phase, but She can be a fine protection by lowering the opponent's monster attack by 100 for each spell card in the GY.   Controller/Defenders   2x Mystic Mine: everyone knows what this card does : stall your opponent to death. Combined with  Sky Striker Ace - Hayate this card became a real problem to deal with.    2x Wave-Motion Cannon: best option to  use in conjunction with Mystic Mine.    2x Solemn Judgment : your big "no no" when you start second and a excellent card in the mid game    2x Effect veiler + 2x Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion: your primaries hand trap to stop your opponent from playing. Belle to stop plays in the GY, Veiler to negate any monster effect.    2x There Can Be Only One: Decks based on one type card  (Salamagreat for example) suffers a lot with this majestic stall card.   3x Sky Striker Mecha - Widow Anchor: one of the most broken card in this archetype, that spell can steal a monster in the opponent’s field to use for attack , link folder or  furthermore can negate an effect of a monster if you wish,becoming  one of the most vesertale cards in your deck.   3x Sky Striker Mecha - Shark Cannon: Your D.D. Crow in spell form, can disturrupted some plays of your opponent,and also can special summon one of this opponent's monsters  in you side of the field to generate advantage (Masked HERO Dark Law For exemple) or to be a  link folder.   1x Sky Striker Ace - Zeke + 1x Sky Striker Ace - Kaina: Both have a similar role that can be exploited in the opponent’s turn. Kaina can be summoned by the effect of Raye in the  opponent’s turn and not allowing a monster to attack. Zeke on the other hand, can be used with Roze and Raye to banish a monster in your summon.   1x Knightmare Unicorn: Combined with I:P Masquerena , this monster can remove a target card with a non- destruction effect in the opponent's turn, making a formidable monster.   Utility cards   1x Raigeki: A classical card and a budget one   1x Sky Striker Maneuver - Afterburners!+ 1X Sky Striker Maneuver - Afterburners!:  Pop a monster and a set spell/trap card , respectively   1x Knightmare Phoenix: Pop a set spell/trap card and a good target for the stolen monster to link off.   1x I:P Masquerena:  To get in you big link monster with some protection in the opponent's turn.   1x Topologic Zeroboros:  If everything goes wrong , you can always blow up the field with this bad boy.   Side deck   Almost every card in my side deck it’s self explanatory except Sky Striker Maneuver - Scissors Cross  that can add  a main deck  sky striker monster to your hand from the Gy.   Conclusion   This deck can be a little brick but it’s one of the most versatile decks in this game, with great recovery, control  and it can be  annoying  too. I hope you enjoy this deck from the bottom of my heart and you too can make this Colegial war girls shine once more.
